<!doctype html>
<meta charset="utf8">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="./spec.css">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/highlight.js/8.4/styles/github.min.css">
<script src="./spec.js"></script>
<pre class="metadata">
title: Runtime Types
stage: 0
contributors: Sirisian
</pre>

<emu-intro id="sec-intro">
  <h1>Introduction</h1>
  <p>This proposal adds an optional static type system to ECMAScript. Its types are values at run time and are enforced there: a typed binding rejects a value outside its type, a conversion between numeric types is written explicitly rather than performed silently, and the type of a value is available through reflection. Annotations are optional and additive, so a program that does not use them keeps its current meaning.</p>

  <p>The system is deliberately close to the value-type discipline of systems languages. It adds sized integers, floats, and decimals; value-type classes with a defined in-memory layout; operator overloading; generics specialized by monomorphization; and types as first-class, interned values that ordinary code can compute with and reflect on. None of this is visible to a program that does not opt in.</p>

  <p>This document is the normative specification. It is written against the design, which, together with the rationale, the full set of extensions, and worked examples, is maintained in the <a href="https://github.com/sirisian/ecmascript-types">design repository</a>. Readers new to the proposal should start there; this document formalizes what that material describes.</p>

  <emu-note>
    <p>The specification is under active construction. The clauses below establish the shape of the document; normative text is added phase by phase, following the specification plan in the design repository. Until a section is filled in here, the corresponding behaviour is defined only by the design documents.</p>
  </emu-note>
</emu-intro>

<emu-clause id="sec-runtime-types">
  <h1>Runtime Types</h1>
  <p>This clause and its subclauses define the runtime type system as a set of additions to and revisions of the ECMAScript specification. The work is organized into the phases described in the design repository's specification plan: the static type-checking framework; the grammar of type expressions; the type universe; conversions; runtime enforcement; typed declarations, operators, functions, and classes; the type-object and reflection API; and the numeric library. Extensions (SIMD, generics, decorators, primitive metadata, and the rest) are specified as independent additions layered on this core.</p>

  <p>Each addition is expressed as an insertion into or revision of the referenced edition of ECMAScript, so that this document reads as a patch against that specification rather than a restatement of it. As clauses are written they will appear here in the order of the underlying ECMAScript specification, cross-referenced to the sections they modify.</p>

  <emu-clause id="sec-type-system-foundations">
    <h1>Type System Foundations</h1>
    <p>This clause defines the machinery the rest of the specification builds on: the representation of a type, the structural identity that interns types into unique values, the subtyping and assignability relations, the static type of an expression, compile-time evaluation of a type expression, and the reporting of type errors. It introduces no user-facing syntax; the productions and library that use this machinery are added by later clauses.</p>

    <emu-note>
      <p>ECMAScript defines runtime behaviour through abstract operations and a limited set of static semantics, chiefly Early Errors, but it has no framework for assigning a type to an expression or relating two types. This clause establishes that framework. Because a type in this proposal is also a value, a single notion, the Type Object, serves both as the entity the type checker reasons about and as the value a program observes.</p>
    </emu-note>

    <emu-clause id="sec-types-and-type-objects">
      <h1>Types and Type Objects</h1>
      <p>A <dfn id="type-record">Type Record</dfn> is a Record used by this specification to describe an ECMAScript type. Each Type Record has a [[Kind]] field and the additional fields listed for that kind in <emu-xref href="#table-type-record-kinds"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-type-record-kinds" caption="Type Record Kinds">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>[[Kind]]</th><th>Additional Fields</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>~any~</td><td>(none)</td><td>The dynamic type. Any value is assignable to it, and a value of the ~any~ type is assignable to any type subject to a run-time check (<emu-xref href="#sec-requiretype"></emu-xref>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~void~</td><td>(none)</td><td>The type of the absence of a value.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~primitive~</td><td>[[Name]] (a String), [[Arguments]] (a List of Type Records and other values)</td><td>A built-in value type such as `uint8` or `float64`, together with any type or value arguments, for example the width of `int.&lt;N&gt;`. The primitive types are enumerated in the type universe clause.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~literal~</td><td>[[Value]] (a String, Number, Boolean, or BigInt), [[Base]] (a Type Record)</td><td>A literal type: the type whose one value is [[Value]], a subtype of its [[Base]] (<emu-xref href="#sec-literal-types"></emu-xref>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~nominal~</td><td>[[Declaration]] (a Parse Node), [[Arguments]] (a List of Type Records and other values)</td><td>A class, interface, or enum type, identified by the declaration that introduced it, together with the arguments of a generic instantiation. [[Arguments]] is empty where the declaration is not generic.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~union~</td><td>[[Members]] (a List of Type Records)</td><td>A union type. A value belongs to it if it belongs to any member.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~intersection~</td><td>[[Members]] (a List of Type Records)</td><td>An intersection type. A value belongs to it if it belongs to every member.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~tuple~</td><td>[[Elements]] (a List of Tuple Element Records)</td><td>A tuple type of position-wise element types, each element carrying its spread flag and its default.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~array~</td><td>[[Element]] (a Type Record), [[Extent]] (a non-negative integer or ~dynamic~)</td><td>An array type. [[Extent]] is the fixed length of a `[N].&lt;T&gt;`, or ~dynamic~ for a `[].&lt;T&gt;`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~object~</td><td>[[Properties]] (a List of Property Type Records), [[IndexSignatures]] (a List of Index Signature Records)</td><td>A structural object type or interface type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~function~</td><td>[[Signatures]] (a List of Signature Records)</td><td>A function type. It has more than one signature when the function is overloaded.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~reference~</td><td>[[Target]] (a Type Record)</td><td>A reference to a storage location holding a value of the target type, as introduced by `ref`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>~application~</td><td>[[Builder]] (a function), [[Arguments]] (a List of Type Records, TypeParameter Parse Nodes, and ECMAScript language values)</td><td>A deferred compile-time application: a call of a compile-time-evaluable function at least one of whose arguments involves an unbound generic parameter, carried as a type until specialization evaluates it (<emu-xref href="#sec-compile-time-evaluability"></emu-xref>).</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The structured fields referenced above, a Property Type Record, an Index Signature Record, a Signature Record, and a Tuple Element Record, are defined by the clauses that introduce object types, function types, and arrays and tuples. This clause depends only on Type Records being comparable and canonicalizable, which the operations below provide for every kind.</p>
      </emu-note>

      <p>A <dfn id="type-object">Type Object</dfn> is an ECMAScript object that denotes a type. Every Type Object has a [[TypeRecord]] internal slot whose value is a canonical Type Record (<emu-xref href="#sec-canonicalizetype"></emu-xref>). A type name or type expression in expression position evaluates to a Type Object, and reflection returns one.</p>

      <p>Type Objects are interned. <emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref> maps each canonical Type Record to a unique Type Object, so two Type Objects denote the same type if and only if they are the same value. Consequently comparing two Type Objects with IsStrictlyEqual returns *true* exactly when they denote the same type, and a Type Object may be used as a property key or a key in a Map or Set to key on a type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The observable behaviour of a Type Object, including how it exposes its own structure to reflection, is defined by <emu-xref href="#sec-reflection"></emu-xref>. The remainder of the type system uses only its [[TypeRecord]] and its identity.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-structural-identity">
      <h1>Structural Identity</h1>
      <p>Two types are the same when they have the same structure, with one exception: a ~nominal~ type is identified by its declaration, so two classes with identical members are still different types. This clause defines that notion and the canonical form that makes it decidable and internable. A pair of Type Records is carried through the recursive comparisons as a List so that comparison of a recursive type terminates; each such pair is represented as a Record with a [[First]] field and a [[Second]] field.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-sametype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          SameType (
            _s_: a Type Record,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _s_ and _t_ denote the same type.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. Return SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_, _t_, &laquo; &raquo;).
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-sametypewithassumptions" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          SameTypeWithAssumptions (
            _s_: a Type Record,
            _t_: a Type Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _s_ and _t_ denote the same type, treating each pair in _assumptions_ as already established so that comparison of recursive types terminates.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _s_ and _t_ are the same Record, return *true*.
          1. If _assumptions_ contains a Record _p_ such that _p_.[[First]] is _s_ and _p_.[[Second]] is _t_, return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~nominal~ and _s_.[[Declaration]] is an enum declaration, then
            1. If IsSubtype(the underlying type of _s_.[[Declaration]], _t_, _assumptions_) is *true*, return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~literal~, return IsSubtype(_s_.[[Base]], _t_, _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is not _t_.[[Kind]], return *false*.
          1. Set _assumptions_ to the list-concatenation of _assumptions_ and &laquo; the Record { [[First]]: _s_, [[Second]]: _t_ } &raquo;.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~any~ or _s_.[[Kind]] is ~void~, return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~primitive~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Name]] is not _t_.[[Name]], return *false*.
            1. Return SameArgumentList(_s_.[[Arguments]], _t_.[[Arguments]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~literal~, then
            1. If SameValue(_s_.[[Value]], _t_.[[Value]]) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_.[[Base]], _t_.[[Base]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~application~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Builder]] and _t_.[[Builder]] are not the same function, return *false*.
            1. Return SameArgumentList(_s_.[[Arguments]], _t_.[[Arguments]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~nominal~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Declaration]] and _t_.[[Declaration]] are not the same Parse Node, return *false*.
            1. Return SameArgumentList(_s_.[[Arguments]], _t_.[[Arguments]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~union~ or _s_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~, return SameTypeList(_s_.[[Members]], _t_.[[Members]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~tuple~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Elements]] and _t_.[[Elements]] do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
            1. For each integer _i_ such that 0 &le; _i_ and _i_ &lt; the number of elements of _s_.[[Elements]], do
              1. Let _p_ be _s_.[[Elements]][_i_].
              1. Let _q_ be _t_.[[Elements]][_i_].
              1. If _p_.[[Rest]] is not _q_.[[Rest]], return *false*.
              1. If _p_.[[Initial]] is ~none~ or _q_.[[Initial]] is ~none~, then
                1. If _p_.[[Initial]] is not ~none~ or _q_.[[Initial]] is not ~none~, return *false*.
              1. Else if SameValue(_p_.[[Initial]], _q_.[[Initial]]) is *false*, then
                1. Return *false*.
              1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_p_.[[Type]], _q_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~array~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Extent]] is not _t_.[[Extent]], return *false*.
            1. Return SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_.[[Element]], _t_.[[Element]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~reference~, return SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_.[[Target]], _t_.[[Target]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~function~, return SameFunctionType(_s_, _t_, _assumptions_).
          1. Assert: _s_.[[Kind]] is ~object~.
          1. Return SameObjectType(_s_, _t_, _assumptions_).
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>SameTypeList holds when two Lists of Type Records have the same length and are position-wise the same under _assumptions_. SameArgumentList is SameTypeList extended to compare non-type arguments, such as an array extent, with SameValue. SameObjectType (<emu-xref href="#sec-sameobjecttype"></emu-xref>) and SameFunctionType (<emu-xref href="#sec-samefunctiontype"></emu-xref>) compare the members of an ~object~ or ~function~ type. Because a canonical ~union~ or ~intersection~ has its members in a fixed order (<emu-xref href="#sec-canonicalizetype"></emu-xref>), position-wise comparison of members is sufficient.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-sametypelist" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          SameTypeList (
            _a_: a List of Type Records,
            _b_: a List of Type Records,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _a_ and _b_ have the same length and are position-wise the same type under _assumptions_.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _a_ and _b_ do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
          1. For each integer _i_ such that 0 &le; _i_ and _i_ &lt; the number of elements of _a_, do
            1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_a_[_i_], _b_[_i_], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
          1. Return *true*.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-sameargumentlist" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          SameArgumentList (
            _a_: a List,
            _b_: a List,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _a_ and _b_ have the same length and equal elements, comparing Type Record elements as types under _assumptions_, Parse Node elements by being the same Parse Node, compound compile-time constants by structural equivalence (<emu-xref href="#sec-deferred-applications"></emu-xref>), and other elements with SameValue.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _a_ and _b_ do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
          1. For each integer _i_ such that 0 &le; _i_ and _i_ &lt; the number of elements of _a_, do
            1. Let _x_ be _a_[_i_].
            1. Let _y_ be _b_[_i_].
            1. If _x_ is a Type Record and _y_ is a Type Record, then
              1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_x_, _y_, _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Else if _x_ is a Type Record or _y_ is a Type Record, then
              1. Return *false*.
            1. Else if _x_ is a Parse Node and _y_ is a Parse Node, then
              1. If _x_ and _y_ are not the same Parse Node, return *false*.
            1. Else if _x_ is a Parse Node or _y_ is a Parse Node, then
              1. Return *false*.
            1. Else if _x_ and _y_ are compound compile-time constants, then
              1. If _x_ and _y_ are not structurally equivalent (<emu-xref href="#sec-deferred-applications"></emu-xref>), return *false*.
            1. Else if SameValue(_x_, _y_) is *false*, then
              1. Return *false*.
          1. Return *true*.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-canonicalizetype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          CanonicalizeType (
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): a Type Record
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the canonical form of _t_. Canonical Type Records that denote the same type are the same Record, which is what lets <emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref> intern them.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~union~ or _t_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~, then
            1. Let _members_ be a new empty List.
            1. For each element _m_ of _t_.[[Members]], do
              1. Let _c_ be CanonicalizeType(_m_).
              1. If _c_.[[Kind]] is _t_.[[Kind]], then
                1. For each element _n_ of _c_.[[Members]], append _n_ to _members_.
              1. Else,
                1. Append _c_ to _members_.
            1. Remove from _members_ each element that is the same type (SameType) as an element occurring earlier in _members_.
            1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~ and _members_ contains an element whose [[Kind]] is ~union~ and whose [[Members]] is empty, return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: &laquo; &raquo; } (the `never` type; see <emu-xref href="#sec-never-type"></emu-xref>).
            1. If _members_ has exactly one element, return that element.
            1. Order the elements of _members_ according to a total order on canonical Type Records fixed by this specification.
            1. Return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: _t_.[[Kind]], [[Members]]: _members_ }.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~tuple~, then
            1. Let _elements_ be a new empty List.
            1. For each element _e_ of _t_.[[Elements]], do
              1. Append the Tuple Element Record { [[Type]]: CanonicalizeType(_e_.[[Type]]), [[Rest]]: _e_.[[Rest]], [[Initial]]: _e_.[[Initial]] } to _elements_.
            1. Return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~tuple~, [[Elements]]: _elements_ }.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~array~, return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~array~, [[Element]]: CanonicalizeType(_t_.[[Element]]), [[Extent]]: _t_.[[Extent]] }.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~reference~, return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~reference~, [[Target]]: CanonicalizeType(_t_.[[Target]]) }.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~literal~, return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~literal~, [[Value]]: _t_.[[Value]], [[Base]]: CanonicalizeType(_t_.[[Base]]) }.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~application~, then
            1. Let _args_ be a new empty List.
            1. For each element _a_ of _t_.[[Arguments]], do
              1. If _a_ is a Type Record, append CanonicalizeType(_a_) to _args_.
              1. Else, append _a_ to _args_.
            1. Return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~application~, [[Builder]]: _t_.[[Builder]], [[Arguments]]: _args_ }.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~object~ or _t_.[[Kind]] is ~function~, return the canonical form of _t_ defined alongside that kind, with each contained Type Record canonicalized.
          1. Return _t_.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Flattening merges a nested union into its parent, and likewise for intersection; de-duplication and the fixed order make member order insignificant, so `A | B` and `B | A` canonicalize to one Record and, after interning, one Type Object. A ~nominal~, ~primitive~, ~any~, or ~void~ Type Record is already canonical apart from canonicalizing the Type Records in its [[Arguments]], which the recursion reaches when they occur. Recursion terminates because a cycle in a type passes through a ~nominal~ position, which is canonical without descending into its declaration. Flattening is also what removes a `never` member from a union: the member is an empty union, so it contributes nothing, and `T | never` canonicalizes to `T` with no rule naming the case. The intersection step above is the one algebraic fact about `never` that does not fall out this way (<emu-xref href="#sec-never-type"></emu-xref>).</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-gettypeobject" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          GetTypeObject (
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): a Type Object
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the unique Type Object that denotes the type described by _t_.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. Let _canonical_ be CanonicalizeType(_t_).
          1. If the type-object intern table contains a Type Object _existing_ such that SameType(_existing_.[[TypeRecord]], _canonical_) is *true*, return _existing_.
          1. Let _obj_ be a new Type Object whose [[TypeRecord]] internal slot is _canonical_.
          1. Add _obj_ to the type-object intern table.
          1. Return _obj_.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>The intern table is a specification device; an implementation may realize it in any way that yields the same identities. Interning is per-Agent: Type Objects, like other objects, are not shared across Agents except through the mechanisms of the threading extension.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-subtyping-and-assignability">
      <h1>Subtyping and Assignability</h1>
      <p><dfn id="subtyping">Subtyping</dfn> relates a more specific type to a more general one. <dfn id="assignability">Assignability</dfn> is the relation the type checker applies at an assignment, an argument, or a return: it is subtyping, widened at the boundary with the ~any~ type. Because this proposal performs no implicit numeric widening, a ~primitive~ type is a subtype of no other numeric type. It is a subtype of itself, of the ~any~ type, and of the same primitive bearing fewer metadata arguments, since a metadata parameterization refines the type it parameterizes rather than being a different type: `Meter` is a `float32.&lt;{ m: 1 }&gt;` and is a subtype of `float32`, which is what makes `m instanceof float32` *true*.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-issubtype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsSubtype (
            _s_: a Type Record,
            _t_: a Type Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether every value of the type _s_ is a value of the type _t_, treating each pair in _assumptions_ as already established so that comparison of recursive types terminates. The initial call passes an empty List for _assumptions_.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_, _t_, _assumptions_) is *true*, return *true*.
          1. If _assumptions_ contains a Record _p_ such that _p_.[[First]] is _s_ and _p_.[[Second]] is _t_, return *true*.
          1. Set _assumptions_ to the list-concatenation of _assumptions_ and &laquo; the Record { [[First]]: _s_, [[Second]]: _t_ } &raquo;.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
            1. For each element _m_ of _s_.[[Members]], do
              1. If IsSubtype(_m_, _t_, _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
            1. For each element _m_ of _t_.[[Members]], do
              1. If IsSubtype(_s_, _m_, _assumptions_) is *true*, return *true*.
            1. Return *false*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~, then
            1. For each element _m_ of _t_.[[Members]], do
              1. If IsSubtype(_s_, _m_, _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~, then
            1. For each element _m_ of _s_.[[Members]], do
              1. If IsSubtype(_m_, _t_, _assumptions_) is *true*, return *true*.
            1. Return *false*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is not _t_.[[Kind]], return *false*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~primitive~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Name]] is not _t_.[[Name]], return *false*.
            1. If _s_.[[Arguments]] is a metadata parameterization of _t_.[[Arguments]], as the primitive metadata extension defines, return *true*.
            1. Return *false*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~nominal~, then
            1. If _t_.[[Declaration]] is _s_.[[Declaration]], return SameArgumentList(_s_.[[Arguments]], _t_.[[Arguments]], _assumptions_).
            1. If _t_.[[Declaration]] is an ancestor of _s_.[[Declaration]] in the class and interface hierarchy, then
              1. Return the result of comparing _t_.[[Arguments]] against the arguments _s_ supplies to _t_.[[Declaration]] through the hierarchy, with SameArgumentList.
            1. Return *false*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~array~, then
            1. If _t_.[[Extent]] is not ~dynamic~ and _t_.[[Extent]] is not _s_.[[Extent]], return *false*.
            1. Return SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_.[[Element]], _t_.[[Element]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~tuple~, then
            1. If _s_.[[Elements]] and _t_.[[Elements]] do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
            1. For each integer _i_ such that 0 &le; _i_ and _i_ &lt; the number of elements of _s_.[[Elements]], do
              1. Let _p_ be _s_.[[Elements]][_i_].
              1. Let _q_ be _t_.[[Elements]][_i_].
              1. If _p_.[[Rest]] is not _q_.[[Rest]], return *false*.
              1. If IsSubtype(_p_.[[Type]], _q_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~reference~, return SameTypeWithAssumptions(_s_.[[Target]], _t_.[[Target]], _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~function~, return IsFunctionSubtype(_s_, _t_, _assumptions_).
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~object~, return IsObjectSubtype(_s_, _t_, _assumptions_).
          1. Return *false*.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>A ~literal~ type is a subtype of its base and of everything its base is a subtype of, which is what makes `'on'` usable where a `string` is required while `string` is not usable where `'on'` is. A ~tuple~'s [[Rest]] flags must match position for position, and its defaults take part in identity but not in subtyping; the finer relation between tuples whose arities differ through defaults or rests is not yet given.</p>
          <p>A deferred ~application~ is a subtype only of itself and of the `any` type. Before specialization nothing finer than identity is known about its result, so nothing finer is assumed: two mentions of one deferred call are one type by interning, and two different calls are unrelated until they evaluate. No step above names the kind because none needs to; an ~application~ source reaches the final step for every target but itself and `any`.</p>
          <p>A generic class is invariant in its arguments, so `Map.&lt;string, uint8&gt;` is a subtype of no other instantiation of `Map`. This is the conservative choice and the only one that is sound for a mutable container, since a `Map.&lt;string, uint8&gt;` used as a `Map.&lt;string, number&gt;` would accept a Number into storage typed `uint8`. Whether a generic parameter may be declared covariant or contravariant, as it may in C# and Kotlin, is a question for the generics extension; nothing here forecloses it, and the step above is what such a declaration would relax.</p>
          <p>The kind-specific steps record the variance chosen by this proposal: a ~nominal~ type is a subtype along its declared inheritance; an ~array~ is invariant in its element, and a fixed-length array is a subtype of the ~dynamic~-length array of the same element; a ~tuple~ is covariant position-wise; a ~reference~ is invariant in its target. IsObjectSubtype (<emu-xref href="#sec-isobjectsubtype"></emu-xref>) applies width subtyping to properties and depth subtyping through a `readonly` one; IsFunctionSubtype (<emu-xref href="#sec-isfunctionsubtype"></emu-xref>) applies contravariant-parameter, covariant-return subtyping to signatures. An enum type is additionally a subtype of its underlying type (<emu-xref href="#sec-enums"></emu-xref>). The justification for each choice is given by the clause that introduces the corresponding feature.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-isassignable" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsAssignable (
            _s_: a Type Record,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether a value of the type _s_ may be assigned where the type _t_ is expected. This is the relation checked at bindings, arguments, and returns.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~any~ or _t_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return *true*.
          1. Return IsSubtype(_s_, _t_, &laquo; &raquo;).
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>When _s_ is the ~any~ type and _t_ is not, assignability holds but the value's membership in _t_ is not known statically; a check is inserted at the boundary (<emu-xref href="#sec-requiretype"></emu-xref>) that throws a *TypeError* if the value is not of the type _t_. When _t_ is the ~any~ type, no check is required. This two-part treatment, static where the types are known and a run-time check at the ~any~ boundary, is the gradual character of the system: it is why an untyped program keeps its behaviour while a typed one is checked.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-static-type-of-an-expression">
      <h1>The Static Type of an Expression</h1>
      <p>The <dfn id="static-type">Static Type</dfn> of an expression is the Type Record the type checker assigns to it. It is a syntax-directed operation defined by cases over the expression grammar. Each later clause that adds or modifies an expression form gives the Static Type for that form; the cases established by this clause are those that do not depend on a feature introduced later, listed in <emu-xref href="#table-static-type-base"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-static-type-base" caption="Static Type of Base Expression Forms">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Expression form</th><th>Static Type</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>A numeric literal</td><td>The ~primitive~ type named `"number"`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A string literal</td><td>The ~primitive~ type named `"string"`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*true* or *false*</td><td>The ~primitive~ type named `"boolean"`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*null*</td><td>The type named `"null"`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A reference to a binding</td><td>The declared type of that binding, or the ~any~ type if the binding has none.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A type name or type expression in expression position</td><td>The ~primitive~ type named `"type"`.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The Static Type of a numeric literal given here is its type in the absence of a contextual type. Literal propagation, by which a literal takes the type its context requires, so that `0` in a `uint8` position is a `uint8`, refines this and is defined by the conversions clause. The Static Types of the remaining expression forms, including operators, calls, array and object literals, and `this`, are given by the clauses that specify those forms; until a form is specified, its Static Type is the ~any~ type.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-compile-time-evaluability">
      <h1>Compile-Time Evaluation</h1>
      <p>Because a type is a value, a type annotation may be an expression that computes one (<emu-xref href="#sec-computed-types"></emu-xref>); an expression whose computation can be carried out during type checking is <dfn id="compile-time-evaluable">compile-time evaluable</dfn>. This clause defines when such an expression may be evaluated, when it is, what its evaluation may do, and what carries its result before it can run: the evaluability discipline, the deferred application that stands for a call whose generic arguments are not yet bound, the evaluation of a call with memoization and a fixpoint for recursion, and the budget that bounds the whole.</p>

      <p>Evaluation is confined to checking and reads declarations rather than run-time bindings. A top-level type-position expression evaluates during the compilation of its module, with the other static semantics and before the evaluation of any module in the graph begins. A type-position expression inside a generic declaration evaluates at each specialization, once every generic parameter it reads is bound. The callee of a call resolves through imports to a function declaration, whose body these semantics interpret, so no module's run-time evaluation is required or performed by evaluating a type.</p>

      <p>No operation of this specification evaluates such an expression before every generic parameter it reads is bound: a builder runs strictly after inference binds its arguments, never inside that inference, and never during overload resolution or narrowing. The computed constraints of <emu-xref href="#sec-computed-constraints"></emu-xref> are the measure of this boundary rather than an exception to it, since a constraint over `T` runs after `T` is inferred and before the parameter it constrains is, which is after everything it reads. The only checker-visible effect of a compile-time-evaluable function is the Type Object it evaluates to at a type position. This is a design invariant, stated so that later ergonomic pressure has something to push against.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-iscompiletimeevaluable" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsCompileTimeEvaluable (
            _expr_: a Parse Node,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _expr_ can be evaluated during type checking, reading only values known at that time.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _expr_ is a literal, return *true*.
          1. If _expr_ is a reference to a binding, then
            1. If the binding is a parameter of the function under evaluation, or a local binding of that function, return *true*.
            1. If the binding is immutable and its initializer is compile-time evaluable, return *true*.
            1. If the binding is a value generic parameter or a type generic parameter, return *true*.
            1. Return *false*.
          1. If _expr_ is a function call, then
            1. Let _callee_ be the expression that _expr_ calls.
            1. Let _args_ be the List of argument expressions of _expr_.
            1. If IsCompileTimeEvaluable(_callee_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. If _callee_ does not denote a compile-time-evaluable function, return *false*.
            1. For each element _arg_ of _args_, do
              1. If IsCompileTimeEvaluable(_arg_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If every operand of _expr_ is compile-time evaluable and the result of _expr_'s operator is determined by its operands, return *true*.
          1. Return *false*.
        </emu-alg>

        <p>A <dfn id="compile-time-evaluable-function">compile-time-evaluable function</dfn> is one whose body reads only its parameters, its own local bindings, immutable bindings whose initializers are compile-time evaluable, and other compile-time-evaluable functions. It may create local state and mutate it. Its body contains no `await`, no `yield`, no direct or indirect `eval`, no use of the Function constructor, and no construction of a Proxy; regular expressions are within the fragment. It performs no input or output and reads no ambient mutable state, none of which it can name under the reading rule above, which is why the discipline is a property of what the code can name rather than a wall around what it does.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>This is the same notion the `where` clauses and metadata annotations of the extensions require, and it is what lets a `switch` over a generic parameter be evaluated to a type during checking. A function that is not compile-time evaluable remains an ordinary function in expression position; only its use in type position is restricted. Local mutation is admitted because an accumulator array or a visited `Set` is how a walk over a type is written; shared module-level mutable state is not evaluable and is rejected statically, which also disposes of the hand-rolled memo cache, since the memoization of <emu-xref href="#sec-evaluatebuildercall"></emu-xref> is the supported mechanism and is observably equivalent. Fixing the fragment's grammar and semantics as a normative implementation target in its own right, with a conformance suite, is future annex work; the discipline above is the normative boundary this specification relies on.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-deferred-applications">
        <h1>Deferred Applications</h1>
        <p>A call whose arguments involve an unbound generic parameter cannot evaluate yet, and is carried as a type: the ~application~ Type Record of <emu-xref href="#table-type-record-kinds"></emu-xref>. The <dfn id="deferred-application-record">deferred application Type Record</dfn> of a |ComputedType| has [[Builder]] the function its callee resolves to and, for each argument in order, an element of [[Arguments]] that is: the TypeParameter Parse Node where the argument is a reference to an unbound generic parameter; the deferred application Type Record where the argument is itself a |ComputedType| reading one; and otherwise the argument's compile-time value, a Type Object contributing its [[TypeRecord]].</p>

        <p>Identity is by that key. SameTypeWithAssumptions compares two ~application~ Records by builder identity and SameArgumentList, and Type Objects are interned, so two mentions of `partial(T)` in one generic body are one Type Object before anything is known about `T`. At specialization, each TypeParameter Parse Node among the [[Arguments]] is replaced by the parameter's binding, and the application evaluates by <emu-xref href="#sec-evaluatebuildercall"></emu-xref>.</p>

        <p>Two compound compile-time constants, arrays or plain objects of compile-time constants, are <dfn id="structurally-equivalent">structurally equivalent</dfn> when they have the same shape and their leaves are pairwise SameValue, Type Objects comparing by identity. A compound constant argument contributes to an application's identity by structural equivalence rather than by reference, so `pick(User, ['id', 'name'])` written twice is one application although the array is a fresh object at each occurrence.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>An unbound parameter is represented by its declaring Parse Node rather than by a Type Record kind of its own, because a parameter is never a type by itself anywhere this specification currently reaches; what a bare parameter annotation denotes inside a generic body belongs to the generics work, and the hook for it is recorded in <emu-xref href="#table-extension-hooks"></emu-xref>. Structural equivalence for compound constants is the value semantics the Composites proposal gives tuples and records; it is stated directly here so that this specification does not depend on that proposal, and can defer to it if it advances.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-evaluatebuildercall" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          EvaluateBuilderCall (
            _f_: a compile-time-evaluable function,
            _args_: a List,
          ): either a normal completion containing a Type Object or a throw completion
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It evaluates one type-level call, with memoization and a fixpoint for recursion.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. Let _key_ be CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~application~, [[Builder]]: _f_, [[Arguments]]: _args_ }).
          1. If the evaluation memo contains an entry for _key_, return that entry's Type Object.
          1. If the in-flight List contains _key_, then
            1. If no placeholder exists for _key_, let the placeholder for _key_ be a fresh Type Object, created without interning and distinguished from every other value.
            1. Return the placeholder for _key_.
          1. Append _key_ to the in-flight List.
          1. Let _result_ be Completion(the evaluation of the body of _f_ with the elements of _args_ as its arguments under the semantics of this clause).
          1. Remove _key_ from the in-flight List.
          1. Let _value_ be ? _result_.
          1. If _value_ is not a Type Object, throw a *TypeError* exception.
          1. If a placeholder exists for _key_, then
            1. If _value_ is the placeholder for _key_, throw a *TypeError* exception.
            1. Let _final_ be the Type Record obtained from _value_.[[TypeRecord]] by replacing each position that holds the placeholder with a reference back to the type being defined, forming a cyclic Type Record.
            1. If no replaced position is a reference position, throw a *TypeError* exception.
            1. Set _value_ to GetTypeObject(_final_).
          1. Record _value_ in the evaluation memo for _key_.
          1. Return _value_.
        </emu-alg>

        <p>The <dfn id="evaluation-memo">evaluation memo</dfn> is a specification-level map from canonical ~application~ Type Records to Type Objects, and the in-flight List tracks the keys under evaluation. Each distinct key evaluates once per program; every later occurrence, in any module, yields the same interned Type Object. An implementation may realize both devices in any way that yields these results.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>The fixpoint is what makes a builder work on a recursive type with no API surface: a builder mapping over a type that references itself re-enters itself with the same key, receives the placeholder, and the placeholder resolves at return into the same kind of named-back-edge cyclic type that a recursive alias produces from syntax, validated by the same cycle rule (<emu-xref href="#sec-type-alias-declarations"></emu-xref>). The two throws distinguish the two failures: a call whose entire result is its own placeholder learnt nothing and is unproductive recursion, and a cycle resolved at a position that embeds the layout inline would demand an infinite layout. A recursion that never repeats a key, a genuinely infinite family, is not caught here; it runs into the budget of <emu-xref href="#sec-evaluation-budget"></emu-xref>. This mechanism is the computational twin of the coinductive assumption Lists that SameTypeWithAssumptions and IsSubtype already carry.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-evaluation-budget">
        <h1>The Evaluation Budget</h1>
        <p>Evaluation under this clause is metered by two host-defined limits: a count of evaluation steps and a count of constructed Type Records, each per top-level type-position evaluation. For a given source text, two hosts either produce, position for position, the same interned types, or at least one reports a type error: the limits decide whether compilation fails, never what it produces.</p>

        <p>Exhaustion is not an abrupt completion the evaluated code can observe. No `try` statement within the evaluation handles it; the evaluation is abandoned, and EvaluateToTypeObject of the containing type-position expression is ~empty~, with a diagnostic naming the outermost call and the deepest frames.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>Making exhaustion catchable inside evaluation would let a program's types depend on the host's limits: the same source would elaborate differently under a large budget and a small one, and the memo would cache whichever answer came first, which is nondeterminism through the error channel. Graceful degradation therefore has to be deterministic and structural: a builder takes an explicit cap as an argument and computes the identical type on every host, rather than falling back when fuel runs out. Bounding a deliberately Turing-complete type language by limits has precedent; the concrete default magnitudes are an open question the design records.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-evaluatetotypeobject" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          EvaluateToTypeObject (
            _expr_: a Parse Node,
          ): either a Type Object or ~empty~
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It evaluates _expr_, which appears in type position, to the Type Object it denotes, or defers it, or returns ~empty~ if it does not evaluate to one.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If IsCompileTimeEvaluable(_expr_) is *false*, return ~empty~.
          1. If _expr_ is a |ComputedType| and _expr_ reads a generic parameter that is not bound, return GetTypeObject(the deferred application Type Record of _expr_ (<emu-xref href="#sec-deferred-applications"></emu-xref>)).
          1. Let _result_ be Completion(the evaluation of _expr_ during type checking in which each call of a compile-time-evaluable function is performed by EvaluateBuilderCall).
          1. If _result_ is an abrupt completion, return ~empty~.
          1. Let _value_ be _result_.[[Value]].
          1. If _value_ is not a Type Object, return ~empty~.
          1. Return _value_.
        </emu-alg>
        <p>It is a type error if an expression appears in type position and EvaluateToTypeObject of it is ~empty~ (<emu-xref href="#sec-type-errors"></emu-xref>). When the ~empty~ arises from an abrupt completion whose value is an Error, the type error's diagnostic carries that Error's message, prefixed by the source text of the type-position expression; when it arises from the budget, the diagnostic is the one <emu-xref href="#sec-evaluation-budget"></emu-xref> describes. Diagnostic content is not observable to the evaluated program.</p>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Evaluation during type checking uses the ordinary evaluation semantics of the operators and calls involved, restricted to the compile-time-evaluable fragment, so no separate evaluator is defined. Because enum and sealed-class exhaustiveness is checked, a `switch` used to map a value to a type covers every case its argument can take and therefore yields a Type Object rather than *undefined*. A thrown exception becoming the diagnostic is the design's authored-error story: a builder states its own misuse message, which an erased type language cannot.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-errors">
      <h1>Type Errors</h1>
      <p>A <dfn id="type-error">type error</dfn> is a violation of the type system detected by the type checker: an assignment whose source is not assignable to its target, a call whose arguments match no signature, a type annotation that is not compile-time evaluable, and the like. The clauses that follow state such a violation with the phrase &ldquo;it is a type error if&rdquo;.</p>

      <p>A type error that is determinable statically, from the types of a construct alone, is an Early Error. Like other Early Errors it is detected before the containing code is evaluated, and a source text that contains one is rejected rather than evaluated. This is how the type system composes with the existing static semantics: type checking is an additional body of static semantic rules over the same Parse Nodes, applied at the same time as Early Error checking.</p>

      <p>A check that cannot be resolved statically, because a value reaches a typed position only as the ~any~ type, is deferred to run time. <emu-xref href="#sec-runtime-enforcement"></emu-xref> specifies where these deferred checks are inserted and what they throw: a *TypeError* when a value is not of the required type, and a *RangeError* when a numeric value is outside the range of its type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The design documents sometimes describe a statically-determinable violation, such as assigning a `uint32` to a `uint8` binding, as a &ldquo;*TypeError*&rdquo;. This specification realizes such a violation as an Early Error, and reserves a thrown *TypeError* for the ~any~ boundary and other genuinely dynamic checks. The distinction is observable: an Early Error rejects the source text before any of it runs, whereas a thrown *TypeError* occurs during evaluation. Treating a statically-determinable type violation as a whole-source rejection matches a strict, check-before-run type system; whether some violations should instead be deferred to a thrown error at the offending operation is a decision to be settled as the feature clauses are written.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-type-grammar">
    <h1>Grammar</h1>
    <p>This clause adds the syntax for writing a type. It is grammar only: it defines what may be written and where, while the meaning of each form is given by the clauses that follow. Every production here is additive, and every construct it introduces is a syntax error in the current language, so no source text changes meaning.</p>

    <emu-note>
      <p>The type grammar is a separate grammar from the expression grammar, reached from expression contexts only through the annotation and operator productions of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-annotations"></emu-xref> and <emu-xref href="#sec-types-in-expression-position"></emu-xref>. Keeping the two apart is what lets a type use `|`, `&amp;`, `{`, and `(` with meanings unrelated to their expression counterparts.</p>
    </emu-note>

    <emu-clause id="sec-lexical-grammar-for-types">
      <h1>Lexical Grammar</h1>

      <emu-clause id="sec-type-punctuators">
        <h1>Punctuators</h1>
        <p>Two punctuators are added. Neither token sequence occurs in any currently valid source text, which is what allows them to be added without changing the meaning of an existing program.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          Punctuator ::
            OptionalChainingPunctuator
            <ins>TypePunctuator</ins>
            OtherPunctuator

          <ins>TypePunctuator :: one of
            `.&lt;` `:=`</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <emu-note>
          <p>`.&lt;` introduces a type argument list (<emu-xref href="#sec-type-references"></emu-xref>). Today a `.` must be followed by an identifier name, a private name, or a numeric part of a literal, so `.&lt;` is never produced by valid source text. The leading `.` is what distinguishes generic application from a comparison: `a.&lt;b&gt;(c)` cannot be read as `a &lt; b &gt; (c)`, which is the ambiguity that prevents the bare angle-bracket form. Because a numeric literal is lexed by longest match, `1.&lt;2` still lexes as the literal `1.` followed by `&lt;`, and so continues to mean a comparison.</p>
          <p>`:=` introduces a typed initializer or a conversion (<emu-xref href="#sec-types-in-expression-position"></emu-xref>). A `:` immediately followed by `=` does not occur in valid source text.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-input-element-type">
        <h1>The InputElementType Goal Symbol</h1>
        <p>A type argument list is delimited by `&lt;` and `&gt;`, and type arguments nest, so a source text may end one list immediately inside another. Under the ordinary lexical goals the two closing punctuators would be lexed as a single `&gt;&gt;` token. A goal symbol is therefore added in which `&gt;` is always a single punctuator.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>InputElementType ::
            WhiteSpace
            LineTerminator
            Comment
            CommonToken
            RightBracePunctuator</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <p>The |InputElementType| goal symbol is used in all syntactic grammar contexts where a |TypeArguments| or a |TypeParameters| is being parsed, between its opening `.&lt;` or `&lt;` and its closing `&gt;`. When this goal symbol is used, the punctuators `&gt;&gt;`, `&gt;&gt;&gt;`, `&gt;=`, `&gt;&gt;=`, and `&gt;&gt;&gt;=` are not recognized; a `&gt;` is lexed as the single-character punctuator `&gt;`.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>This is the same device the specification already uses to lex `/` differently where a regular expression may appear. It resolves the nesting problem lexically rather than by a parser rule, so `Map.&lt;string, [].&lt;uint8&gt;&gt;` closes both lists. A shift operator inside a type argument list must be parenthesized, which is only relevant to a value argument, since a shift cannot otherwise appear in a type.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-imaginary-literals">
        <h1>Imaginary Literals</h1>
        <p>An imaginary literal is a numeric literal with the suffix `i`, denoting a value on the imaginary axis. The suffix occupies the slot a numeric literal followed immediately by an identifier start occupies today, which is a syntax error, and is the slot the `n` suffix of a BigInt literal already uses.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          NumericLiteral ::
            DecimalLiteral
            DecimalBigIntegerLiteral
            <ins>DecimalImaginaryLiteral</ins>
            NonDecimalIntegerLiteral[+Sep]
            NonDecimalIntegerLiteral[+Sep] BigIntLiteralSuffix
            LegacyOctalIntegerLiteral

          <ins>DecimalImaginaryLiteral ::
            DecimalLiteral ImaginaryLiteralSuffix</ins>

          <ins>ImaginaryLiteralSuffix :: `i`</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <emu-note>
          <p>Unlike the BigInt suffix, which attaches only to an integer literal, the imaginary suffix attaches to any |DecimalLiteral|, so `4i`, `2.5i`, and `1e3i` are all imaginary literals. The rule that the source character following a numeric literal must not be an identifier start continues to apply, so `4if` remains a syntax error. The type of an imaginary literal is defined by the complex numbers extension.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-expressions">
      <h1>Type Expressions</h1>
      <p>A |Type| is the syntax of a type. Union and intersection compose types, and the remaining forms are primary.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        <ins>Type[Yield, Await] :
          UnionType[?Yield, ?Await]
          FunctionType[?Yield, ?Await]

        UnionType[Yield, Await] :
          IntersectionType[?Yield, ?Await]
          UnionType[?Yield, ?Await] `|` IntersectionType[?Yield, ?Await]

        IntersectionType[Yield, Await] :
          PrimaryType[?Yield, ?Await]
          IntersectionType[?Yield, ?Await] `&amp;` PrimaryType[?Yield, ?Await]

        PrimaryType[Yield, Await] :
          PredefinedType
          LiteralType
          TypeReference[?Yield, ?Await]
          ComputedType[?Yield, ?Await]
          KeyOfType[?Yield, ?Await]
          ArrayOrTupleType[?Yield, ?Await]
          ObjectType[?Yield, ?Await]
          ReferenceType[?Yield, ?Await]
          CoverParenthesizedTypeAndFunctionTypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await]

        PredefinedType : one of
          `void` `null`

        LiteralType :
          NumericLiteral
          `-` NumericLiteral
          StringLiteral
          `true`
          `false`

        ReferenceType[Yield, Await] :
          `ref` PrimaryType[?Yield, ?Await]

        KeyOfType[Yield, Await] :
          `keyof` PrimaryType[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
      </emu-grammar>

      <emu-note>
        <p>|FunctionType| is an alternative of |Type| rather than of |UnionType|, because a function type's return extends as far to the right as it can: `(string) =&gt; uint32 | null` returns `uint32 | null`. A function type is therefore not by itself a member of a union or an intersection, and putting one in a union requires parenthesizing it. That is true on either side, so the order of a union's members never matters.</p>
        <p>`void` and `null` are reserved words and so cannot be reached through |TypeReference|, which is why they are given their own production. The other built-in type names, `uint8` and the rest, are ordinary identifiers and are reached through |TypeReference|; they are shadowable, so a program that declares its own binding named `uint8` is unaffected.</p>
        <p>|ReferenceType| takes a |PrimaryType| operand, so `ref uint8 | null` is a union of `ref uint8` and `null`. `ref` is a contextual keyword: it is a valid identifier today, so `ref` followed by a token that cannot begin a type is an identifier.</p>
        <p>`keyof` is likewise a contextual keyword, and a |KeyOfType| binds tighter than union and intersection, so `keyof A | B` is the union of `keyof A` and `B`. Its result is the union of the operand's key types, one literal type per named member. The full definition over each kind is given by <emu-xref href="#sec-keyof"></emu-xref>, producing a union of the literal types of <emu-xref href="#sec-literal-types"></emu-xref>.</p>
      </emu-note>

      <emu-clause id="sec-type-references">
        <h1>Type References and Type Arguments</h1>
        <p>A type reference names a type, optionally applying type arguments to it. Generic application always uses `.&lt;`, in a type and in an expression alike.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>TypeReference[Yield, Await] :
            TypeName[?Yield, ?Await] TypeArguments[?Yield, ?Await]?

          TypeName[Yield, Await] :
            IdentifierReference[?Yield, ?Await]
            TypeName[?Yield, ?Await] `.` IdentifierName

          TypeArguments[Yield, Await] :
            `.&lt;` TypeArgumentList[?Yield, ?Await] `,`? `&gt;`

          TypeArgumentList[Yield, Await] :
            TypeArgument[?Yield, ?Await]
            TypeArgumentList[?Yield, ?Await] `,` TypeArgument[?Yield, ?Await]

          TypeArgument[Yield, Await] :
            Type[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <emu-note>
          <p>Because `.&lt;` is a single punctuator, a qualified name and an application are told apart lexically: in `Temporal.Unit` the `.` is followed by an identifier, while in `Map.&lt;string, uint8&gt;` the `.&lt;` opens an argument list, so a |TypeName| cannot extend across it.</p>
          <p>A type argument is written as a |Type| even when it is a value, as the width in `int.&lt;8&gt;` and the lane count in `vector.&lt;float32, 4&gt;` are. A numeric or string literal argument is a |LiteralType|, and a name that resolves to a value generic parameter is a |TypeReference|, so the syntax need not distinguish the two; the clause on generics decides which a given parameter expects. A value argument that is a computed expression, such as an arithmetic combination of value generic parameters, has no syntax here and is an open question for the generics clause. A computed type (<emu-xref href="#sec-computed-types"></emu-xref>) gives the computation a spelling as a call, so a builder can stand in where the argument position cannot compute; whether the argument position itself should is the part that remains open.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-computed-types">
        <h1>Computed Types</h1>
        <p>A type position admits a call. The callee is written as a type reference and the arguments as ordinary expressions, so `partial(User)`, `keysOf(T)`, and `pick(User, ['id', 'name'])` are types, as is a call of a call where a function returns a function that computes one.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>ComputedType[Yield, Await] :
            TypeReference[?Yield, ?Await] Arguments[?Yield, ?Await]
            ComputedType[?Yield, ?Await] Arguments[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <p>A |ComputedType| is a compile-time type expression and is governed by <emu-xref href="#sec-compile-time-evaluability"></emu-xref>: the call must be compile-time evaluable, and the type the |ComputedType| denotes is the Type Object that EvaluateToTypeObject returns for it. A call that is not evaluable, that completes abruptly, or that does not produce a Type Object is a type error by the rule stated there.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>The form is additive twice over. Every position in which a |Type| may appear is new syntax, so no existing program contains one; and within the grammar of this specification a |TypeName| followed by `(` derived nothing before this production, so no program written against the earlier grammar changes meaning either. Disambiguation costs one token: after a type reference, `.&lt;` opens type arguments, `(` opens a call, and any other token ends the reference.</p>
          <p>Only a call is admitted, deliberately. The design's rule is that an expression evaluating to a Type Object during checking is a valid type, and the call is the one expression form the type grammar needs to reach all of it: a conditional over IsAssignable, a map over a union's members, or any richer computation is a function away, written inside the builder rather than inline in the annotation. Keeping the surface to one form also keeps the evaluability requirement attached to one production.</p>
          <p>The same call in expression position is an ordinary call and needs nothing from this clause: a builder is an ordinary function, and calling it at run time yields the same interned Type Object the type position denotes. This production makes the call writable where a type is required; it does not change what the call is.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-keyof">
        <h1>Static Semantics of keyof</h1>
        <p>A |KeyOfType| denotes GetTypeObject of the Type Record that KeyTypesOf returns for the Type Record its operand denotes. It is a type error if KeyTypesOf of that Record is ~empty~.</p>

        <emu-clause id="sec-keytypesof" type="abstract operation">
          <h1>
            KeyTypesOf (
              _t_: a Type Record,
            ): either a Type Record or ~empty~
          </h1>
          <dl class="header">
            <dt>description</dt>
            <dd>It returns the type of the keys of _t_, or ~empty~ where _t_ has no keys.</dd>
          </dl>
          <emu-alg>
            1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~object~, then
              1. Let _keys_ be a new empty List.
              1. For each element _p_ of _t_.[[Properties]], do
                1. If _p_.[[Key]] is a String, append the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~literal~, [[Value]]: _p_.[[Key]], [[Base]]: the Type Record of the String type } to _keys_.
              1. For each element _x_ of _t_.[[IndexSignatures]], append _x_.[[KeyType]] to _keys_.
              1. Return CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: _keys_ }).
            1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~, then
              1. Let _keys_ be a new empty List.
              1. For each element _m_ of _t_.[[Members]], do
                1. Let _k_ be KeyTypesOf(_m_).
                1. If _k_ is ~empty~, return ~empty~.
                1. Append _k_ to _keys_.
              1. Return CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: _keys_ }).
            1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
              1. If _t_.[[Members]] is empty, return _t_.
              1. Let _first_ be KeyTypesOf(_t_.[[Members]][0]).
              1. If _first_ is ~empty~, return ~empty~.
              1. Let _kept_ be a List of the union members of _first_: the elements of _first_.[[Members]] where _first_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, and &laquo; _first_ &raquo; otherwise.
              1. For each integer _i_ such that 1 &le; _i_ and _i_ &lt; the number of elements of _t_.[[Members]], do
                1. Let _k_ be KeyTypesOf(_t_.[[Members]][_i_]).
                1. If _k_ is ~empty~, return ~empty~.
                1. Remove from _kept_ each element that is not assignable (IsAssignable) to _k_.
              1. Return CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: _kept_ }).
            1. Return ~empty~.
          </emu-alg>
          <emu-note>
            <p>These are the rules of the design's `keysOf`, which computes the same function over a Type Object held in a variable, so the operator and the kit function cannot drift apart. A union's keys are the common keys, computed by keeping the first arm's keys that remain assignable to each further arm's, which is what lets the literal `'x'` survive against an arm whose keys come from a `string`-keyed index signature. An intersection's keys are the union of its members' keys. A Symbol key contributes nothing, pending the design's symbol literal types. A kind with no keys is ~empty~ and a type error, matching the kit's authored throw; `keyof never` is `never` by the empty-union step, a case the kit's fold does not reach and the design should state.</p>
          </emu-note>
        </emu-clause>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-array-and-tuple-types">
        <h1>Array and Tuple Types</h1>
        <p>An array type is a fixed or dynamic count of elements of one type, and a tuple type is a fixed count of individually typed positions. Both are written in brackets, and are told apart by whether a type argument list follows the closing bracket.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>ArrayOrTupleType[Yield, Await] :
            `[` `]`
            `[` `]` TypeArguments[?Yield, ?Await]
            `[` ArrayExtent[?Yield, ?Await] `]` TypeArguments[?Yield, ?Await]
            `[` TupleElementList[?Yield, ?Await] `,`? `]`

          ArrayExtent[Yield, Await] :
            AssignmentExpression[+In, ?Yield, ?Await]

          TupleElementList[Yield, Await] :
            TupleElement[?Yield, ?Await]
            TupleElementList[?Yield, ?Await] `,` TupleElement[?Yield, ?Await]

          TupleElement[Yield, Await] :
            Type[?Yield, ?Await] Initializer[+In, ?Yield, ?Await]?
            `...` Type[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <emu-note>
          <p>`[]` alone is the array of `any`, which is the bound of the array and tuple family, so a type parameter constrained by it is satisfied by any array or tuple. `[].&lt;T&gt;` is a dynamic array, `[N].&lt;T&gt;` a fixed one, and `[T1, T2]` a tuple. A tuple's trailing position may carry a default through |Initializer|, and a tuple may spread another tuple or an array type at either end.</p>
          <p>The first three alternatives and the fourth are distinguished only after the closing `]`, by whether a |TypeArguments| follows, and their bracketed contents belong to different grammars: an extent is an expression and a tuple element list is a list of types. A single-element case such as `[uint8]` therefore cannot be resolved by bounded lookahead. An implementation may parse the bracketed text under a cover grammar and refine it once the following token is known, as the specification already does for parenthesized expressions and arrow parameters. Whether the two forms should instead be distinguished by their opening bracket is a question worth settling before the syntax is final.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-object-types">
        <h1>Object Types</h1>
        <p>An object type describes a value by its members. It is the inline form of an interface.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>ObjectType[Yield, Await] :
            `{` `}`
            `{` TypeMemberList[?Yield, ?Await] TypeMemberSeparator? `}`

          TypeMemberList[Yield, Await] :
            TypeMember[?Yield, ?Await]
            TypeMemberList[?Yield, ?Await] TypeMemberSeparator TypeMember[?Yield, ?Await]

          TypeMemberSeparator : one of
            `,` `;`

          TypeMember[Yield, Await] :
            PropertyName[?Yield, ?Await] `?`? TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]
            PropertyName[?Yield, ?Await] `?`? MethodSignature[?Yield, ?Await]

          MethodSignature[Yield, Await] :
            TypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await]? `(` FunctionTypeParameterList[?Yield, ?Await]? `,`? `)` TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <emu-note>
          <p>Members are separated by either `,` or `;`, and a trailing separator is permitted, so both `{ x: float32, y: float32 }` and `{ x: float32; y: float32; }` are written. A `?` marks an optional member.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-function-types">
        <h1>Function Types</h1>
        <p>A function type is a parameter list and a return type. Its parameters may be named or unnamed, and may carry the `ref` and rest modifiers a declaration's parameters carry.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>FunctionType[Yield, Await] :
            FunctionTypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await] `=&gt;` Type[?Yield, ?Await]

          FunctionTypeParameters[Yield, Await] :
            CoverParenthesizedTypeAndFunctionTypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await]

          CoverParenthesizedTypeAndFunctionTypeParameters[Yield, Await] :
            `(` `)`
            `(` FunctionTypeParameterList[?Yield, ?Await] `,`? `)`

          FunctionTypeParameterList[Yield, Await] :
            FunctionTypeParameter[?Yield, ?Await]
            FunctionTypeParameterList[?Yield, ?Await] `,` FunctionTypeParameter[?Yield, ?Await]

          FunctionTypeParameter[Yield, Await] :
            `ref`? Type[?Yield, ?Await]
            `ref`? BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] `?`? TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]
            `...` BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]
            `...` Type[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <p>When the production <emu-grammar>PrimaryType : CoverParenthesizedTypeAndFunctionTypeParameters</emu-grammar> is recognized, the interpretation of |CoverParenthesizedTypeAndFunctionTypeParameters| is refined using <emu-grammar>ParenthesizedType : `(` Type `)`</emu-grammar>; it is a type error if the cover does not match that refinement.</p>

        <emu-grammar type="definition">
          <ins>ParenthesizedType[Yield, Await] :
            `(` Type[?Yield, ?Await] `)`</ins>
        </emu-grammar>

        <emu-note>
          <p>`(uint8)` is a parenthesized type and `(uint8) =&gt; uint8` is a function type, and the two are told apart by the token after the closing parenthesis, exactly as a parenthesized expression is told from arrow parameters. The cover grammar is the same device the specification already uses there.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-parameters">
      <h1>Type Parameters</h1>
      <p>A generic declaration introduces its parameters in angle brackets. Declaration uses `&lt;`, while application uses `.&lt;`, so the ambiguity that application avoids does not arise at a declaration, where no expression may appear.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        <ins>TypeParameters[Yield, Await] :
          `&lt;` TypeParameterList[?Yield, ?Await] `,`? `&gt;`

        TypeParameterList[Yield, Await] :
          TypeParameter[?Yield, ?Await]
          TypeParameterList[?Yield, ?Await] `,` TypeParameter[?Yield, ?Await]

        TypeParameter[Yield, Await] :
          BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] TypeParameterConstraint[?Yield, ?Await]? TypeParameterDefault[?Yield, ?Await]?

        TypeParameterConstraint[Yield, Await] :
          `:` Type[?Yield, ?Await]
          `extends` Type[?Yield, ?Await]

        TypeParameterDefault[Yield, Await] :
          `=` Type[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
      </emu-grammar>

      <emu-note>
        <p>A parameter written with `:` is a value generic parameter, whose argument is a value of the named type, as `W` and `H` are in `class GridArray&lt;W: uint32, H: uint32&gt;`. A parameter written with `extends` is a type parameter bounded by a type, as `T` is in `T extends []`. A parameter with neither is an unbounded type parameter. The `where` clause that further constrains a parameter is defined by the generics extension.</p>
      </emu-note>

      <emu-clause id="sec-computed-constraints">
        <h1>Computed Constraints and Literal Inference</h1>
        <p>The |Type| of a |TypeParameterConstraint| or a |TypeParameterDefault| may be a |ComputedType| (<emu-xref href="#sec-computed-types"></emu-xref>) that reads parameters declared earlier in the same |TypeParameterList|. It is a type error for it to read the parameter it belongs to or one declared later in the list.</p>

        <p>Parameters bind left to right. At a use of the generic declaration, whether through explicit arguments or through inference from a call, the first parameter is bound, then the next parameter's constraint is evaluated by <emu-xref href="#sec-compile-time-evaluability"></emu-xref> over the bindings so far, then that parameter is bound and checked against its evaluated constraint, and so on down the list. Within the declaration itself, before any parameter is bound, such a constraint is carried as the deferred application of <emu-xref href="#sec-deferred-applications"></emu-xref>.</p>

        <p>Where a parameter's evaluated constraint is a literal type or a union of literal types (<emu-xref href="#sec-literal-types"></emu-xref>), the binding inferred for that parameter from a call argument is the literal type of the argument's value, not the widened base. The binding is then checked against the constraint as any binding is.</p>

        <emu-note>
          <p>This is the one placement of a builder call that needs a sentence of new specification, and the one inference rule builders ask for. `function pluck&lt;T, K: keysOf(T)&gt;(o: T, key: K): indexed(T, K)` reads in order: infer `T` from `o`, evaluate `keysOf(T)` over that binding, and infer `K` from the second argument literally, so `pluck(user, 'name')` binds `K` to the literal type `'name'` and the return type evaluates to that property's type. The constraint does double duty, checking the argument and cueing the literal inference, which is the cue `K extends keyof T` gives an erased system. It is a rule about constraints rather than a hook: no user code runs inside the inference of the parameters the constraint reads, and a mistaken argument fails the ordinary constraint check, with the evaluated union available to the diagnostic.</p>
          <p>A constraint that is a value type binds a value, as the note above says of `W: uint32`; a constraint that is a union of literal types binds a literal type, whose value is recoverable from it. The design's kit reads that value back out constantly, which suggests these are one mechanism seen from two sides, a binding to the literal type with the value as its view, and the generics work should state which is primitive.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-annotations">
      <h1>Type Annotations</h1>
      <p>A type annotation attaches a type to a binding, a parameter, a return, or a class member. This clause adds the annotation and the positions that accept it; the meaning of an annotation in each position is given by the declarations, functions, and classes clauses.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        <ins>TypeAnnotation[Yield, Await] :
          `:` Type[?Yield, ?Await]

        TypedInitializer[In, Yield, Await] :
          `:=` AssignmentExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>A binding may carry an annotation, or a typed initializer that infers the binding's type from its initializer.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        LexicalBinding[In, Yield, Await] :
          BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> Initializer[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]?
          <ins>BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] TypedInitializer[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
          BindingPattern[?Yield, ?Await] Initializer[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]

        VariableDeclaration[In, Yield, Await] :
          BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> Initializer[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]?
          <ins>BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] TypedInitializer[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
          BindingPattern[?Yield, ?Await] Initializer[?In, ?Yield, ?Await]
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>A parameter may carry an annotation, an optional marker, and a `ref` modifier.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        FormalParameter[Yield, Await] :
          <ins>`ref`?</ins> BindingElement[?Yield, ?Await]

        SingleNameBinding[Yield, Await] :
          BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] <ins>`?`?</ins> <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> Initializer[+In, ?Yield, ?Await]?
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>A function may carry type parameters and a return annotation.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        FunctionDeclaration[Yield, Await, Default] :
          `function` BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] <ins>TypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> `(` FormalParameters[~Yield, ~Await] `)` <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> `{` FunctionBody[~Yield, ~Await] `}`
          [+Default] `function` <ins>TypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> `(` FormalParameters[~Yield, ~Await] `)` <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> `{` FunctionBody[~Yield, ~Await] `}`
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>A class field may carry an annotation.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        FieldDefinition[Yield, Await] :
          ClassElementName[?Yield, ?Await] <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> Initializer[+In, ?Yield, ?Await]?
      </emu-grammar>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The positions above are representative rather than exhaustive: the remaining function forms, including methods, arrow functions, generators, and class constructors, take the same annotations and are patched by the clauses that specify them. An arrow function's parameter list and return annotation interact with the arrow cover grammar and are given by <emu-xref href="#sec-typed-arrow-functions"></emu-xref>.</p>
        <p>`ref` before a parameter is a contextual keyword. A parameter named `ref` remains valid, since an identifier that is not followed by a token that can begin a binding element is a parameter name; `function f(ref)` therefore continues to declare a parameter named `ref`, while `function f(ref a: int32)` declares a reference parameter named `a`.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-types-in-expression-position">
      <h1>Types in Expression Position</h1>
      <p>A type name is already an expression, since a type is a value, so `uint8` and `Map.&lt;string, uint8&gt;` may be written where a value is expected. The type forms whose syntax collides with the expression grammar cannot: a function type reads as an arrow function, an object type as a block, and a union as a bitwise or. The `type` operator resolves the collision by parsing its operand as a type.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        UnaryExpression[Yield, Await] :
          UpdateExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `delete` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `void` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `typeof` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `+` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `-` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `~` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          `!` UnaryExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          [+Await] AwaitExpression[?Yield]
          <ins>TypeOperatorExpression[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>

        <ins>TypeOperatorExpression[Yield, Await] :
          `type` [no LineTerminator here] Type[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>A conversion converts the value of its left operand to a type, and is written after the value.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        RelationalExpression[In, Yield, Await] :
          ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await] `&lt;` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await] `&gt;` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await] `&lt;=` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await] `&gt;=` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await] `instanceof` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          [+In] RelationalExpression[+In, ?Yield, ?Await] `in` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          [+In] PrivateIdentifier `in` ShiftExpression[?Yield, ?Await]
          <ins>RelationalExpression[?In, ?Yield, ?Await] `:=` Type[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>
      </emu-grammar>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Placing a conversion at |RelationalExpression| gives it the precedence of `instanceof`, so `a + b := uint8` converts the sum, and the right operand being a |Type| means `x := A | B` converts to the union rather than taking the bitwise or of a conversion.</p>
        <p>`type` is a contextual keyword, since a program may already bind the name `type`, and this leaves an ambiguity the design must settle: `type (uint8) =&gt; uint8` is a type operator applied to a function type, while `type (x)` is a call of a function named `type`, and the two agree until the token after the closing parenthesis. An implementation can resolve it with a cover grammar, as it does for arrow parameters, but the committee may prefer a rule that avoids the ambiguity, such as restricting the operand or requiring the operator only where a type cannot otherwise be written. The same question does not arise for the `type` declaration form, whose `type` is followed by a binding identifier. Nor do the computed types of <emu-xref href="#sec-computed-types"></emu-xref> widen the ambiguity: `type f(x)` was a syntax error and is now the operator applied to a computed type, and the unresolved case remains exactly an operand that begins with `(`.</p>
        <p>The operand of `type` is a full |Type| and so extends as far as one reaches: `type A | B` is the union of `A` and `B`, not the bitwise or of `type A` and `B`. A bare name is a type expression, so `type uint8` is a redundant spelling of `uint8`. The extensions that introduce type-position operators, including the `is` operator of the dependent record types extension, use the |Type| production defined here.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-type-universe">
    <h1>The Type Universe</h1>
    <p>This clause adds the value types of this proposal to the ECMAScript language types of <emu-xref href="#sec-ecmascript-language-types"></emu-xref>. For each type it fixes the set of values the type contains and the Type Record (<emu-xref href="#sec-types-and-type-objects"></emu-xref>) that describes it. The operations over these values, the conversions between them, and the literals that produce them are specified by later clauses. This clause settles only what the values are and what the types are called.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-value-types">
      <h1>Value Types</h1>
      <p>A <dfn id="value-type">value type</dfn> is a type whose values are ECMAScript language values that are not Objects. A value of a value type has no identity: two values of the same value type that are the same value are indistinguishable, and nothing observable distinguishes one occurrence of such a value from another. The existing primitive types are value types in this sense, and every type this clause adds is one.</p>

      <p>The values of distinct value types are distinct. Where two types are described below as containing the same mathematical values, each contains its own values representing them: the `uint8` representing 0 and the `uint16` representing 0 are different values of different types, as the Number 1 and the BigInt 1 are today. Every value therefore belongs to exactly one type, which is what lets <emu-xref href="#sec-runtimetypeof"></emu-xref> report it.</p>

      <p>Every type added here is described by a Type Record whose [[Kind]] is ~primitive~, whose [[Name]] is the String naming the type, and whose [[Arguments]] is the List of its type and value arguments. `uint8` is described by the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~primitive~, [[Name]]: *"uint"*, [[Arguments]]: &laquo; 8 &raquo; }, and `vector.&lt;float32, 4&gt;` by { [[Kind]]: ~primitive~, [[Name]]: *"vector"*, [[Arguments]]: &laquo; the Type Record for `float32`, 4 &raquo; }.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Because Type Records are canonicalized and interned (<emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref>), a type written two ways is one Type Object: `int8` and `int.&lt;8&gt;` name the same Type Record and therefore compare strictly equal. The shorthand names of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-names"></emu-xref> are consequently aliases rather than separate types.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-integer-types">
      <h1>Integer Types</h1>
      <p>For each positive integer _N_, `int.&lt;N&gt;` is a value type whose values are the integers from -2<sup>_N_-1</sup> through 2<sup>_N_-1</sup> - 1 inclusive, and `uint.&lt;N&gt;` is a value type whose values are the integers from 0 through 2<sup>_N_</sup> - 1 inclusive. Each has exactly 2<sup>_N_</sup> values. Neither has a negative zero, an infinity, or a NaN.</p>

      <p>_N_ is a value argument, so `int.&lt;8&gt;` and `int.&lt;16&gt;` are distinct types, and the width of a type is recoverable from its Type Record.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Whether _N_ is bounded is an open question. The design gives shorthands only through 128 and uses `uint.&lt;1&gt;` as the lane type of a boolean vector, but nothing above restricts _N_, and an unbounded _N_ obliges every implementation to provide arithmetic at arbitrary width, which is a substantially larger commitment than the named widths imply. Fixing _N_ to a bounded set, to the powers of two, or to a range up to 128 are all defensible; the choice belongs with the committee, and it interacts with the bit-field widths of the memory layout extension, which are the reason a width such as 3 is meaningful at all.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-binary-floating-point-types">
      <h1>Binary Floating-Point Types</h1>
      <p>`float16`, `float32`, `float64`, and `float128` are value types whose values are those of the corresponding IEEE 754-2019 binary interchange formats, with the same treatment of NaN the Number type receives: the many NaN encodings of the format are represented as a single NaN value. Each therefore has 2<sup>_w_</sup> - 2<sup>_p_</sup> + 3 values, where _w_ is the width of the format in bits and _p_ its precision in bits, as given in <emu-xref href="#table-binary-float-types"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-binary-float-types" caption="Binary Floating-Point Types">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>IEEE 754 format</th><th>Width _w_</th><th>Precision _p_</th><th>Values</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>`float16`</td><td>binary16</td><td>16</td><td>11</td><td>63491</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`float32`</td><td>binary32</td><td>32</td><td>24</td><td>4278190083</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`float64`</td><td>binary64</td><td>64</td><td>53</td><td>18437736874454810627</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`float128`</td><td>binary128</td><td>128</td><td>113</td><td>2<sup>128</sup> - 2<sup>113</sup> + 3</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <p>Each of these types has a positive zero and a negative zero, a positive infinity and a negative infinity, and a single NaN, as the Number type does.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`float64` and the Number type have the same set of values but are distinct types, so neither is assignable to the other without a conversion. This is the rule stated for every pair of value types and is not a special case: Number is the type an untyped program computes with, and `float64` is the type a program asks for when it wants that format by name.</p>
        <p>`float80` is listed by the design but is deliberately not defined here. It is not an IEEE 754 interchange format. The 80-bit format it refers to is the x87 double-extended format, whose significand carries an explicit integer bit and therefore admits encodings, the unnormals and pseudo-denormals, that no interchange format has; its in-memory footprint is not 10 bytes on any common ABI but 12 or 16 depending on alignment; and it is unavailable on ARM and on most hardware that is not x86. Since the memory layout extension makes `byteLength` observable, a type whose size differs across platforms cannot be specified the way the other float types can. The options are to define `float80` as IEEE 754 double-extended with a fixed footprint, to drop it, or to admit it as a platform-dependent extension; this needs a decision before the type universe is final.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-decimal-floating-point-types">
      <h1>Decimal Floating-Point Types</h1>
      <p>`decimal32`, `decimal64`, and `decimal128` are value types whose values are those of the corresponding IEEE 754-2019 decimal interchange formats. A finite value of a decimal type is a triple of a sign, an integer coefficient, and an exponent, drawn from the ranges in <emu-xref href="#table-decimal-types"></emu-xref>. Each type additionally has a positive infinity, a negative infinity, and a single NaN.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-decimal-types" caption="Decimal Floating-Point Types">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>IEEE 754 format</th><th>Width</th><th>Coefficient digits</th><th>Exponent range</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>`decimal32`</td><td>decimal32</td><td>32 bits</td><td>7</td><td>-101 through 90</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`decimal64`</td><td>decimal64</td><td>64 bits</td><td>16</td><td>-398 through 369</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`decimal128`</td><td>decimal128</td><td>128 bits</td><td>34</td><td>-6176 through 6111</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <p>Two finite values of a decimal type that have the same numerical value but different exponents are <em>distinct values</em> of the type. The values written `1.0`, `1.00`, and `1.000` are three values of `decimal128`, one for each exponent, and a decimal type therefore preserves the significance of the quantity it was given. IEEE 754 calls such a set of values a cohort.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Preserving trailing zeros is the point of the decimal types: a price given to two places prints to two places, which is what the money types of the primitive metadata extension depend on. The consequence is that the numerical order and the value identity of a decimal type come apart, and the equality operations must choose between them. The design settles two of the three: `==` compares numerical value, so `1.0 == 1.00` is *true*, and SameValueZero compares numerical value, so `1.0` and `1.00` are one key in a Map or a Set rather than two.</p>
        <p>It does not settle SameValue, and the two available answers are both awkward. If SameValue compares numerical value, then `Object.is` cannot distinguish values that print differently, which no other type does. If SameValue distinguishes cohort members, then SameValue and SameValueZero differ on a case unrelated to zero, which is the one distinction their names promise. The parallel with negative zero, where SameValue distinguishes and SameValueZero does not, argues for the latter. This is a decision for the committee and it is recorded here because the type universe is where the cohort becomes observable.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-rational-types">
      <h1>Rational Types</h1>
      <p>For each positive integer _N_, `rational.&lt;N&gt;` is a value type whose values are the exact rational numbers representable as a quotient of two values of `int.&lt;N&gt;`. A value of `rational.&lt;N&gt;` is a pair of a numerator and a denominator, both values of `int.&lt;N&gt;`, such that the denominator is greater than 0 and the greatest common divisor of the numerator and the denominator is 1. Every value of the type is therefore in lowest terms, and each rational number has at most one representation in the type.</p>

      <p>A rational type has no negative zero, no infinity, and no NaN. An operation whose exact result is not representable, including one whose normalized numerator or denominator falls outside `int.&lt;N&gt;`, throws a *RangeError* rather than rounding.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Normalizing on construction is what makes the type a value type in the ordinary sense: without it, one half would have many representations and equality would have to normalize before comparing. It is also what makes the *RangeError* unavoidable, since a sum of two representable rationals can have an unrepresentable normalized denominator. Refusing to round is the distinction between this type and a float; a rational that cannot be represented exactly is an error, not an approximation.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-complex-types">
      <h1>Complex Types</h1>
      <p>For a value type _T_ that is `number` or one of the binary floating-point types, `complex.&lt;T&gt;` is a value type whose values are the ordered pairs of a real part and an imaginary part, each a value of _T_. The number of values of `complex.&lt;T&gt;` is the square of the number of values of _T_.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The width-named shorthands of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-names"></emu-xref> count total bits rather than component bits, following the convention of NumPy and Go, so `complex64` is a pair of `float32` and not a pair of `float64`.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-vector-types">
      <h1>Vector Types</h1>
      <p>For a value type _T_ that is an integer, binary floating-point, or vector type, and a positive integer _N_, `vector.&lt;T, N&gt;` is a value type whose values are the sequences of exactly _N_ values of _T_. _T_ is the lane type and _N_ the lane count. The number of values of `vector.&lt;T, N&gt;` is the number of values of _T_ raised to the power _N_.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>A vector's lane type may itself be a vector, which is how the boolean vectors of the design are built: `boolean8` is `vector.&lt;uint.&lt;1&gt;, 8&gt;`, eight one-bit lanes, and `boolean8x16` is `vector.&lt;boolean8, 16&gt;`. The lane counts an implementation can hold in a register are a matter for the SIMD extension; the type exists for every positive _N_.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-any-type">
      <h1>The any Type</h1>
      <p>`any` is the type of every value. Every ECMAScript language value is a value of the `any` type, and a binding whose type is `any` accepts any value. It is described by the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~any~ }, and it is the type of a binding that carries no annotation, which is what makes an untyped program a program whose bindings are all of the `any` type.</p>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-void-type">
      <h1>The void Type</h1>
      <p>`void` is the type with no values. It is described by the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~void~ }, and it is written as the return type of a function that returns no value. No value is a value of the `void` type, so no binding may have it.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>A call of a function whose return type is `void` evaluates to *undefined*, as a call of a function with no `return` statement does today. The `void` type is the statement that a program must not depend on that result, not a claim that no result exists.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-never-type">
      <h1>The never Type</h1>
      <p>`never` is the type with no values: the union of no members, described by the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: &laquo; &raquo; }. It is not a new kind of type; it is the empty case of a kind the type system already has, admitted as a type in its own right because computation reaches it regardless. A union filtered of its every member is this type, whatever this clause says.</p>

      <p>Its algebra follows from the operations already defined, with no rule specific to it except the one noted last.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>`never` is a subtype of every type. In IsSubtype (<emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>) a source of the ~union~ kind is a subtype when every member is, and a quantification over no members holds.</li>
        <li>No type other than `never` is a subtype of `never`. A target of the ~union~ kind requires some member to accept the source, and there is none.</li>
        <li>`never` is the identity of union. Canonicalization (<emu-xref href="#sec-canonicalizetype"></emu-xref>) flattens a member of the same kind into its parent, and flattening an empty union contributes no members, so `T | never` canonicalizes to `T` with no rule naming the case.</li>
        <li>`never` annihilates intersection: an intersection with a `never` member is `never`. This is the one fact that does not fall out, and CanonicalizeType carries the step for it.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>No value is a value of the `never` type: IsOfType (<emu-xref href="#sec-isoftype"></emu-xref>) over a union with no members is *false* for every value, and DefaultValueOf (<emu-xref href="#sec-defaultvalueof"></emu-xref>) of it is ~none~, so a binding of the type can be neither defaulted nor, since no expression's value can satisfy it, initialized. A value of the `any` type reaching a position of the `never` type fails its boundary check (<emu-xref href="#sec-requiretype"></emu-xref>) for every value. That vacuity is the point: `never` exists to be computed with, as the result of removing every member from a union, not to be inhabited.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Because the empty union canonicalizes to itself and Type Objects are interned (<emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref>), every computation that produces the empty union produces one Type Object, so `never` has the same identity story as every other type. The name is admitted through <emu-xref href="#sec-type-names"></emu-xref> on the same terms as every other built-in type name, so `let x: never;` is writable, and the name is shadowable exactly as `uint8` is. Admitting it does not extend `switch` exhaustiveness, which remains reserved to enums and sealed hierarchies (<emu-xref href="#sec-sealed-classes"></emu-xref>). It is also distinct from the ~empty~ sentinel of the narrowing operations (<emu-xref href="#sec-narrowing"></emu-xref>), which reports a test that cannot succeed as a mistake rather than narrowing to the type with no values.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-literal-types">
      <h1>Literal Types</h1>
      <p>A literal type has exactly one value. It is described by the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~literal~, [[Value]]: _v_, [[Base]]: _b_ }, where _v_ is a String, Number, Boolean, or BigInt and _b_ is the Type Record of the existing language type of which _v_ is a value. A |LiteralType| (<emu-xref href="#sec-type-expressions"></emu-xref>) denotes the literal type of the value it writes: a |StringLiteral| with base `string`, a |NumericLiteral| with base `number` or `bigint` as the literal is written, and `true` or `false` with base `boolean`.</p>

      <p>The one value of a literal type is a value of its base, so the type is a subtype of its base (<emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>), `'on'` is usable where a `string` is required, and a value is of a literal type exactly when it is that value. A union of literal types is the closed set the design's discriminated unions select on, and `keyof` produces one (<emu-xref href="#sec-keyof"></emu-xref>).</p>

      <p>A literal expression whose contextual type (<emu-xref href="#sec-contextual-types"></emu-xref>) is a literal type, or a union or intersection with a literal type among its members, takes the literal type of its own value where that literal type is assignable to the contextual type, so `let a: 'on' | 'off' = 'on';` gives `a` the literal type `'on'`. A contextual type of any other shape leaves the literal to the rules already given for untyped literals, so `let s: string = 'on';` still gives `s` a `string` and `let x: uint8 = 5;` is unchanged.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The base of a numeric literal is `number` however the literal will be used, matching the Static Type a literal takes with no contextual type; a literal type over another numeric type, the `uint8` 3 as a type, is expressible through construction but not through syntax, and its interaction with literal propagation is left with the conversions work. A Symbol cannot be a literal type's value: a symbol has no literal syntax, and admitting computed symbol keys as types is an extension the design records (<emu-xref href="#table-extension-hooks"></emu-xref>).</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-the-type-type">
      <h1>The type Type</h1>
      <p>`type` is the type whose values are the Type Objects (<emu-xref href="#sec-types-and-type-objects"></emu-xref>). It is described by the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~primitive~, [[Name]]: *"type"*, [[Arguments]]: &laquo; &raquo; }, and it is the Static Type of a type name or type expression in expression position (<emu-xref href="#sec-static-type-of-an-expression"></emu-xref>). A function that computes a type annotates its return with it.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`type` is not a value type: its values are Objects, and they have identity. That identity is exactly what interning fixes, so two occurrences of a type expression that denote the same type are the same Type Object rather than merely equal ones. `type` is nonetheless a primitive type in the sense of the Type Record kinds, since it is a named type of the language rather than a structural description of an object's members.</p>
        <p>Because `type` is itself a type, `type` is a value of `type`, and a type argument may be constrained to it, which is what a generic parameter written `T: type` asks for. <emu-xref href="#sec-reflection"></emu-xref> defines what a Type Object exposes.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-existing-language-types">
      <h1>The Existing Language Types</h1>
      <p>The names `number`, `boolean`, `string`, `symbol`, `object`, and `bigint` denote the existing ECMAScript language types of <emu-xref href="#sec-ecmascript-language-types"></emu-xref>: the Number type, the Boolean type, the String type, the Symbol type, the Object type, and the BigInt type respectively. This proposal adds no values to any of them.</p>

      <p>Each is described by a Type Record whose [[Kind]] is ~primitive~ and whose [[Name]] is the name above, except `object`, which is described by { [[Kind]]: ~object~, [[Properties]]: &laquo; &raquo; }, the object type with no required properties, to which every Object is assignable.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`number` is a value type like the rest, so no other numeric type is assignable to it and it is assignable to no other numeric type. It is nonetheless the type an untyped program computes with, and the type a numeric literal takes in the absence of a contextual type (<emu-xref href="#sec-static-type-of-an-expression"></emu-xref>), which is why an unannotated program continues to mean what it means today.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal">
      <h1>Numeric Types</h1>
      <p>The specification already treats a numeric type as a set of values together with a fixed table of abstract operations over them, and defines Number and BigInt that way in <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types"></emu-xref>. Each integer, binary floating-point, decimal floating-point, rational, complex, and vector type is a numeric type in that sense, and provides the operations of that table for which it is defined.</p>

      <p>For a numeric type _T_, the operations are those named in <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types"></emu-xref>: _T_::unaryMinus, _T_::bitwiseNOT, _T_::exponentiate, _T_::multiply, _T_::divide, _T_::remainder, _T_::add, _T_::subtract, _T_::leftShift, _T_::signedRightShift, _T_::unsignedRightShift, _T_::lessThan, _T_::equal, _T_::sameValue, _T_::sameValueZero, _T_::bitwiseAND, _T_::bitwiseXOR, _T_::bitwiseOR, and _T_::toString. A numeric type need not define every operation; one it does not define is not applicable to its values, and an operator that would use it is a type error. The definitions are given by <emu-xref href="#sec-operators"></emu-xref> and <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-library"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Reusing this table rather than introducing a parallel one is what lets the existing operator semantics carry over unchanged. The specification generalized these operations from Number to two types when BigInt was added, and the shape it arrived at, an operator dispatching on the numeric type of its operands with no implicit conversion between types, is the shape this proposal needs. What this clause adds is more numeric types, not a new mechanism.</p>
        <p>The table was written for types that are closed under their operations and totally ordered, and not every type here is either. A complex type has no `lessThan`, since the complex numbers are not ordered. A vector type's comparisons return a vector of lane results rather than a Boolean, which is why the SIMD extension gives them their own return type rather than reusing `lessThan`. A rational type's operations can fail where a float's would round. These are the cases <emu-xref href="#sec-which-operations-each-family-defines"></emu-xref> settles, and they are the reason the table above is a list of what may be defined rather than what must be.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-names">
      <h1>Type Names</h1>
      <p>Each type of this clause is denoted by a name. The generic names `int`, `uint`, `rational`, `complex`, and `vector` denote a type when applied to arguments. The remaining names in <emu-xref href="#table-type-name-shorthands"></emu-xref> are shorthands, each denoting the same Type Record as its expansion and therefore, after interning, the same Type Object.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-type-name-shorthands" caption="Type Name Shorthands">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Shorthand</th><th>Expansion</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>`int8`, `int16`, `int32`, `int64`, `int128`</td><td>`int.&lt;8&gt;`, `int.&lt;16&gt;`, `int.&lt;32&gt;`, `int.&lt;64&gt;`, `int.&lt;128&gt;`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`uint8`, `uint16`, `uint32`, `uint64`, `uint128`</td><td>`uint.&lt;8&gt;`, `uint.&lt;16&gt;`, `uint.&lt;32&gt;`, `uint.&lt;64&gt;`, `uint.&lt;128&gt;`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`boolean1`</td><td>`uint.&lt;1&gt;`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`boolean8`, `boolean16`, `boolean32`, `boolean64`</td><td>`vector.&lt;boolean1, 8&gt;` and so on for 16, 32, and 64 lanes</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`rational`</td><td>`rational.&lt;64&gt;`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`complex64`, `complex128`, `complex`</td><td>`complex.&lt;float32&gt;`, `complex.&lt;float64&gt;`, `complex.&lt;number&gt;`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`never`</td><td>the union of no members, the `never` type (<emu-xref href="#sec-never-type"></emu-xref>)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>_T_`x`_N_, as in `int8x16`, `uint32x4`, `float32x4`, `boolean32x8`</td><td>`vector.&lt;`_T_`, `_N_`&gt;` for the lane type _T_ and lane count _N_ named</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The shorthands are aliases, not distinct types, so `int8 === int.&lt;8&gt;` is *true* and a value of one is a value of the other. `complex` expands through `number` rather than `float64`, so `complex` and `complex128` are distinct types, as `number` and `float64` are.</p>
      </emu-note>

      <emu-note>
        <p>How these names are bound is not settled by the design and is not settled here. Every other part of this proposal is gated by syntax that is an error today, which is the argument that no existing program changes meaning. Type names are not: they are ordinary identifiers, and `number`, `string`, `object`, `boolean`, `symbol`, `any`, and `never` are among the most common identifiers in existing code. The available answers each cost something.</p>
        <p>Binding them as properties of the global object is what the language does for every constructor it has added, and it keeps `var string = "x"` working, since a `var` at global scope reuses an existing property. But the design also asks that these names cannot be reassigned, and a non-writable global property would make that same assignment throw in strict mode and fail silently outside it, so the two requirements cannot both hold. Binding them as immutable lexical declarations of the global scope satisfies the design but makes `var string` at the top level of an existing script a *SyntaxError*, which is not acceptable. Requiring them to be imported, which earlier drafts of the design assumed, has no compatibility cost at all and gives up the ambient spelling the rest of the document uses. Resolving them in type position only, as a language with separate type and value namespaces would, is compatible but contradicts types being values, since the same name must denote the type in expression position for reflection to work.</p>
        <p>This is the one place where the proposal's compatibility argument does not reach, and it deserves a decision and a web-compatibility analysis before Stage 2.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-conversions">
    <h1>Conversions</h1>
    <p>This clause defines when a value of one type becomes a value of another. The governing rule is that it does not: a value of one value type never implicitly becomes a value of another, and every conversion between two distinct value types is written in the source text. This clause states that rule, defines the four things that remain implicit and are not conversions between two typed values, and specifies the explicit conversion that a program writes when it wants one.</p>

    <emu-note>
      <p>The rule exists because no widening is lossless for every pair. `int64` to `float64` loses precision above 2**53, and a language that admits the easy cases has to enumerate the hard ones anyway. Refusing all of them is the rule Rust, Swift, and Go use. It is livable here for the same reason it is livable there: the initializers and arguments that would want a conversion are usually literals, and a literal never needs one (<emu-xref href="#sec-literal-propagation"></emu-xref>).</p>
    </emu-note>

    <emu-clause id="sec-the-conversion-rule">
      <h1>The Conversion Rule</h1>
      <p>At an assignment, an argument, or a return, the source value's type must be assignable to the target type (<emu-xref href="#sec-isassignable"></emu-xref>). Since a ~primitive~ type is a subtype only of itself and of the `any` type, no numeric value type is assignable to another, and a program that requires one to become another states the conversion.</p>

      <p>Four things remain implicit. None is a conversion between two typed values.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-implicit-conversions" caption="What Remains Implicit">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Case</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>A literal in a typed position</td><td>The literal has no type of its own and takes the type its position requires (<emu-xref href="#sec-literal-propagation"></emu-xref>). This is not a conversion; nothing is converted from anything.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A value of the `any` type in a typed position</td><td>The value is checked at the boundary and, if it is a numeric value the target represents exactly, converted; a value the target cannot represent raises a *RangeError*, and one of the wrong type a *TypeError* (<emu-xref href="#sec-requiretype"></emu-xref>). An untyped program has no typed boundaries and so behaves as it does today.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Two parameterizations of one primitive that differ only in their metadata</td><td>They convert by the meta protocol of the primitive metadata extension, whose hooks apply at the same boundaries. `Kilometer` and `Meter` are both `float32`, so this is a conversion within a type rather than between two.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A type that declares a conversion</td><td>The conversion applies at the boundary, because the declaring type opted in (<emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-conversions"></emu-xref>).</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-contextual-types">
      <h1>Contextual Types</h1>
      <p>The <dfn id="contextual-type">contextual type</dfn> of an expression is the type its position requires, or ~none~ where its position requires nothing. It is determined by the position rather than by the expression, and it is what a literal consults.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-contextual-types" caption="Contextual Types by Position">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Position</th><th>Contextual type</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>The |Initializer| of a binding with a |TypeAnnotation|</td><td>The annotated type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>An argument of a call whose callee has a single applicable signature</td><td>The declared type of the corresponding parameter.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>An argument whose corresponding parameter's declared type is a generic parameter</td><td>That parameter's evaluated constraint (<emu-xref href="#sec-computed-constraints"></emu-xref>), or ~none~ where it has none.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>The operand of a `return` in a function with a return annotation</td><td>The annotated return type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>The right operand of an assignment to a target of a known type</td><td>The type of the target.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>An operand of a binary operator whose other operand has a known value type</td><td>The type of the other operand.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>An element of an array or tuple literal in a position of a known array or tuple type</td><td>The element type of that position.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>The operand of an explicit conversion to _T_</td><td>~none~. A conversion converts a value, so its operand is typed on its own.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Any other position</td><td>~none~.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>An argument of an overloaded call has no single contextual type until an overload is chosen, and the choice depends on the argument. The literal ranking of <emu-xref href="#sec-literal-overload-ranking"></emu-xref> is what resolves that circularity for a literal argument. <emu-xref href="#sec-overload-resolution"></emu-xref> specifies the rest of overload resolution.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-literal-propagation">
      <h1>Literal Propagation</h1>
      <p>A numeric literal has no type of its own. In a position whose contextual type is a numeric value type, the literal takes that type, and a literal whose value that type cannot represent is a type error rather than a silent truncation. This refines the Static Type given for a numeric literal in <emu-xref href="#table-static-type-base"></emu-xref>, which is the type of a literal whose contextual type is ~none~.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-literalvalueintype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          LiteralValueInType (
            _literal_: a Parse Node,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): either a value of the type _t_ or ~unrepresentable~
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the value of the type _t_ that _literal_ denotes, or ~unrepresentable~ if _t_ cannot represent it.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. Let _mv_ be the mathematical value denoted by _literal_, as defined by the numeric literal grammar, before any rounding.
          1. If _t_ is an integer type, then
            1. If _mv_ is not an integer, return ~unrepresentable~.
            1. If _t_ has a value representing _mv_ (<emu-xref href="#sec-integer-types"></emu-xref>), return that value.
            1. Return ~unrepresentable~.
          1. If _t_ is a binary floating-point type or the Number type, then
            1. Let _v_ be the result of rounding _mv_ to the nearest value of _t_, with ties to even.
            1. If _v_ is an infinity and _mv_ is finite, return ~unrepresentable~.
            1. Return _v_.
          1. If _t_ is a decimal floating-point type, then
            1. Let _q_ be the number of digits _literal_ writes after its decimal point, negated, adjusted by any exponent _literal_ writes.
            1. Let _c_ be the integer such that _mv_ = _c_ &times; 10**_q_.
            1. If _c_ is outside the coefficient range of _t_, return ~unrepresentable~.
            1. If _q_ is outside the exponent range of _t_, return ~unrepresentable~.
            1. Return the value of _t_ with coefficient _c_ and exponent _q_.
          1. If _t_ is a rational type, then
            1. Let _n_ be the numerator of _mv_ expressed in lowest terms with a positive denominator.
            1. Let _d_ be the denominator of _mv_ expressed in lowest terms with a positive denominator.
            1. Let _ct_ be the integer type of the components of _t_.
            1. If _n_ is a value of _ct_ and _d_ is a value of _ct_, return the value of _t_ with numerator _n_ and denominator _d_.
            1. Return ~unrepresentable~.
          1. Return ~unrepresentable~.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>The mathematical value of a literal is exact. `0.1` denotes one tenth, not the Number nearest to one tenth, so `0.1` in a `decimal64` position is the decimal one tenth and in a `rational` position is 1/10, while in a `float32` position it rounds. This falls out of the specification already defining a literal's mathematical value and rounding it only when producing a Number.</p>
          <p>A decimal type reads its cohort member from the source text rather than from the mathematical value, since `1.0` and `1.00` have the same mathematical value and are different values of the type (<emu-xref href="#sec-decimal-floating-point-types"></emu-xref>). A literal therefore carries its significance into the type, which is what makes a price written to two places a value with two places.</p>
          <p>Representability is exact for an integer, a decimal, and a rational, and is range membership for a float, which rounds. A float is the one family where a literal that is not representable exactly is still accepted, because requiring exactness would reject `0.1` in a `float32` position and no useful program could be written.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <p>The Static Type of a numeric literal whose contextual type is a numeric value type _t_ is _t_. It is a type error if LiteralValueInType(_literal_, _t_) is ~unrepresentable~.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The error is an Early Error (<emu-xref href="#sec-type-errors"></emu-xref>), so `f(256)` where `f` takes a `uint8` does not compile, and neither does `let a: uint8 = 200; a + 300;`, where the literal takes the type of the other operand. This is the difference between a literal and a cast: a cast is an instruction to discard information and truncates, while a literal that does not fit its type is a mistake.</p>
      </emu-note>

      <emu-note>
        <p>One case in the design does not follow this rule. A store to an element of a typed array, as in `array[0] = 300` where `array` is a `[].&lt;uint8&gt;`, is specified to wrap to 44 rather than to be rejected, on the grounds that it is unchanged from what a `Uint8Array` does today. But `[].&lt;uint8&gt;` is new syntax, so no existing program writes that store, and the compatibility argument does not apply to it; meanwhile the literal rule says the same literal in a `uint8` binding does not compile. The two cannot both be right for a literal element. Either the store rejects an out-of-range literal like every other typed position, or the literal rule has an exception for element stores that should be stated. This needs a decision.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-explicit-conversion">
      <h1>Explicit Conversion</h1>
      <p>An explicit conversion is written as a call on the type, `uint8(v)`, or with the conversion operator after the value, `v := uint8` (<emu-xref href="#sec-types-in-expression-position"></emu-xref>). The two are the same operation. A conversion is an instruction to discard information: it truncates, wraps, or rounds as the target requires, and does not fail merely because information is lost.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-convertvalue" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          ConvertValue (
            _value_: an ECMAScript language value,
            _from_: a Type Record,
            _to_: a Type Record,
          ): either a normal completion containing an ECMAScript language value or a throw completion
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It converts _value_, of the type _from_, to the type _to_.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If SameType(_from_, _to_) is *true*, return _value_.
          1. If _from_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return ? RequireType(_value_, _to_).
          1. If _to_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return _value_.
          1. If _from_ is a numeric type and _to_ is a numeric type, return ? NumericConvert(_value_, _from_, _to_).
          1. Let _conversion_ be the user-defined conversion from _from_ to _to_, if one is declared (<emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-conversions"></emu-xref>).
          1. If _conversion_ is not ~empty~, return ? the result of applying _conversion_ to _value_.
          1. If IsAssignable(_from_, _to_) is *true*, return _value_.
          1. Throw a *TypeError* exception.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>The final step is reached only where the operand types are related by no rule above. Where those types are known statically the conversion is rejected as a type error before evaluation (<emu-xref href="#sec-type-errors"></emu-xref>), so the exception is thrown only where a type reaches the conversion dynamically, as when a Type Object computed at run time is called as a function.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-numericconvert" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          NumericConvert (
            _value_: a value of a numeric type,
            _from_: a numeric Type Record,
            _to_: a numeric Type Record,
          ): either a normal completion containing a value of the type _to_ or a throw completion
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It converts _value_ between two numeric types according to <emu-xref href="#table-numeric-conversions"></emu-xref>.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If <emu-xref href="#table-numeric-conversions"></emu-xref> specifies a *RangeError* for _value_ converted from _from_ to _to_, throw a *RangeError* exception.
          1. Let _result_ be the value given by <emu-xref href="#table-numeric-conversions"></emu-xref> for the families of _from_ and _to_.
          1. Assert: _result_ is a value of the type _to_.
          1. Return _result_.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-table id="table-numeric-conversions" caption="Numeric Conversions">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>From</th><th>To</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>integer</td><td>integer of width _M_</td><td>The mathematical value of the source modulo 2**_M_, interpreted as a value of the target. Signed targets wrap in two's complement.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>integer</td><td>binary float</td><td>The source rounded to the nearest value of the target, with ties to even.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>binary float</td><td>integer of width _M_</td><td>If the source is NaN or an infinity, 0. Otherwise the source truncated toward zero, modulo 2**_M_, interpreted as a value of the target.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>binary float</td><td>binary float</td><td>The source rounded to the nearest value of the target, with ties to even. A finite source outside the target's range becomes an infinity of the same sign.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>the Number type</td><td>`float64`, and the reverse</td><td>The source unchanged. The two types have the same values (<emu-xref href="#sec-binary-floating-point-types"></emu-xref>), so the conversion is exact and total.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>rational</td><td>binary float or the Number type</td><td>The exact quotient rounded to the nearest value of the target, with ties to even.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>binary float or the Number type</td><td>rational</td><td>The source's exact value, which is a dyadic rational, in lowest terms. A *RangeError* if its numerator or denominator is not representable, or if the source is NaN or an infinity.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>any numeric type</td><td>decimal</td><td>The source's exact value if it is representable, otherwise rounded to the target's precision. A *RangeError* if the source's exponent is outside the target's range, since a decimal's range is a property of the type rather than of the format.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>decimal</td><td>binary float or integer</td><td>Open. See the note below.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>complex or vector</td><td>any other family, and the reverse</td><td>Not defined by this clause. The complex numbers and SIMD extensions define the conversions of their types.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The design leaves the conversions between the decimal types and the binary types open, noting only that they would need to be clear. They are the hard ones, and the difficulty is not arithmetic but which cohort member results. A `float64` converted to a `decimal128` has an exact decimal expansion, since every binary float is a terminating decimal, but that expansion for 0.1 is a 55-digit value that no `decimal128` can hold, so the result must be rounded and its exponent chosen. Choosing the exponent that preserves the most significance, choosing the shortest expansion that round-trips, and choosing a fixed quantum are all defensible and produce different values. This clause specifies the direction that is exact and leaves the other open deliberately.</p>
        <p>Integer wrapping is the same operation the language already performs when storing to a `Uint8Array`, and the float to integer rule is the shape of the existing ToInt32 and ToUint8 operations: truncate, then reduce modulo the width, with a non-finite source becoming zero. Reusing that shape means a typed array store and an explicit cast agree.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-user-defined-conversions">
      <h1>User-Defined Conversions</h1>
      <p>A type may declare a conversion to or from another type, and a declared conversion applies at an assignment, an argument, and a return, because the type that declares it has opted in. Three forms declare one.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-user-defined-conversions" caption="Declared Conversions">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Form</th><th>Declared on</th><th>Converts</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>A constructor taking one parameter of type _S_</td><td>The target class _T_</td><td>_S_ to _T_. A converting constructor, so `let t: MyType = 1;` is legal when `MyType`'s constructor takes a `float32`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`operator` _T_`()`, a parameterless member</td><td>The source class _S_</td><td>_S_ to _T_, by converting the receiver.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`operator` _T_`(value: ` _S_`)`, a member taking one parameter</td><td>The target _T_</td><td>_S_ to _T_, running with no receiver. This is the form a type declares when its constructor is already spoken for, as `Temporal.Instant`'s is by epoch nanoseconds.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <p>When both a converting constructor and a declared conversion could apply to the same pair, the constructor is preferred. It is a type error if two conversions of the same form apply and neither is more specific.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>A conversion to a tuple type is what makes a class destructurable: a class declaring `operator [number, number, string]()` may be destructured into three bindings, because the destructuring position has a tuple contextual type and the conversion supplies it. The operator overloading extension specifies the declaration syntax; this clause specifies only when a declared conversion is consulted.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-literal-overload-ranking">
      <h1>Literal Overload Ranking</h1>
      <p>A literal argument may satisfy more than one signature of an overloaded function, since it has no type of its own and several parameter types could represent it. The signatures are ranked by the parameter type in the order of <emu-xref href="#table-literal-ranking"></emu-xref>, and the first that can represent the literal is chosen. This ranks literals. An argument that is a typed value is not ranked; it selects the signature its type is assignable to.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-literal-ranking" caption="Literal Ranking of Numeric Types">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Rank</th><th>Types, in order</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1</td><td>`float64`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2</td><td>`float128`, `float80`, `float32`, `float16`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>`decimal128`, `decimal64`, `decimal32`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4</td><td>`uint128`, `uint64`, `uint32`, `uint16`, `uint8`</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5</td><td>`int128`, `int64`, `int32`, `int16`, `int8`</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The ranking is the only place the order of the numeric types matters, and it matters only for a literal. Given `f(a: float32)` and `f(a: uint32)`, the call `f(1)` selects the `float32` signature by the ranking, while `f(uint32(1))` selects the `uint32` one because its argument is typed.</p>
        <p>The ranking as the design gives it does not include `number`, and it should. `number` is the type a numeric literal takes with no contextual type, the type an untyped program computes with, and the type the design's own justification for ranking `float64` first appeals to. Given `f(a: number)` and `f(a: float32)`, the call `f(1)` has no answer above. The natural repair is to rank `number` first, ahead of `float64`, on the same reasoning that ranks `float64` ahead of the rest. It is recorded here rather than assumed because it changes which function a call selects.</p>
        <p>The ranking also omits the rational types and the parameterized widths `int.&lt;N&gt;` and `uint.&lt;N&gt;` for an _N_ that is not a named shorthand, both of which can represent a literal. <emu-xref href="#sec-completing-the-literal-ranking"></emu-xref> says where they fall.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-existing-abstract-conversion-operations">
      <h1>The Existing Abstract Conversion Operations</h1>
      <p>The abstract operations of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-conversion"></emu-xref>, including ToNumber, ToString, ToPrimitive, and ToBoolean, continue to apply to the values of the existing language types unchanged. A value of a type added by this proposal is not an Object, so ToPrimitive returns it unchanged, and ToBoolean of a numeric value is *false* exactly when the value is a zero or a NaN of its type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>ToNumber is where the conversion rule and the existing semantics meet, and the meeting needs care. ToNumber of a `uint8` would produce a Number, which is a conversion between two value types that the rule forbids, so an operator specified in terms of ToNumber cannot simply be applied to a typed operand. The resolution is that an operator on typed operands dispatches through the numeric type protocol (<emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal"></emu-xref>) rather than through ToNumber, so `+a` on a `uint8` is a `uint8` and never a Number. ToNumber retains its meaning for the `any` type, where the operand's type is not known statically and the existing dynamic semantics apply. <emu-xref href="#sec-operator-dispatch"></emu-xref> specifies the dispatch; this note records why ToNumber is not the mechanism.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-runtime-enforcement">
    <h1>Runtime Enforcement</h1>
    <p>A type violation is reported where it is found: at compile time where the types are known, and at run time otherwise. This clause specifies the second half. It defines the runtime type of a value, the test that decides whether a value belongs to a type, the check that enforces a type at a boundary, the boundaries at which that check is inserted, and the circumstances under which it is not needed at all.</p>

    <emu-note>
      <p>The checks exist because of the `any` type. A value reaches a typed position with its type unknown only when it passes through `any`, which is the type of every binding an untyped program declares. Everything else is settled statically. This is what makes the system gradual rather than merely optional: the guarantee a typed program has is not that its author annotated carefully, but that the boundary with untyped code is checked.</p>
    </emu-note>

    <emu-clause id="sec-runtime-type-of-a-value">
      <h1>The Runtime Type of a Value</h1>

      <emu-clause id="sec-runtimetypeof" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          RuntimeTypeOf (
            _value_: an ECMAScript language value,
          ): a Type Record
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the Type Record describing the type of which _value_ is a value.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _value_ is a value of one of the types added by <emu-xref href="#sec-type-universe"></emu-xref>, return that type's Type Record.
          1. If _value_ is *undefined*, return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~primitive~, [[Name]]: *"undefined"*, [[Arguments]]: &laquo; &raquo; }.
          1. If _value_ is *null*, return the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~primitive~, [[Name]]: *"null"*, [[Arguments]]: &laquo; &raquo; }.
          1. If _value_ is a Boolean, a String, a Symbol, a Number, or a BigInt, return the Type Record of the corresponding type named in <emu-xref href="#sec-existing-language-types"></emu-xref>.
          1. If _value_ is a Type Object, return the Type Record for `type`.
          1. Assert: _value_ is an Object.
          1. If _value_ has a [[RuntimeType]] internal slot, return _value_.[[RuntimeType]].
          1. If _value_ is an instance of a class, return the ~nominal~ Type Record of that class.
          1. Return the ~object~ Type Record whose [[Properties]] describes the own properties of _value_ and their declared types, where a property with no declared type has the `any` type.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Every value has exactly one runtime type, because the values of distinct value types are distinct (<emu-xref href="#sec-value-types"></emu-xref>). The `uint8` representing 0 and the `uint16` representing 0 are different values, so `a instanceof uint16` is *false* for a `uint8` binding `a` even though `typeof a` reports *"number"* for both. `typeof` is unchanged by this proposal: it reports the underlying language type, and RuntimeTypeOf is what reports the type of this proposal. <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-typeof"></emu-xref> exposes the latter as `Reflect.typeOf`.</p>
          <p>The [[RuntimeType]] slot is what a Proxy constructed with a type argument carries, so that it reports the type its trap checks enforce rather than the shape of its target. A Proxy constructed without one has no slot and is an ordinary Object.</p>
          <p>The types named *"undefined"* and *"null"* are used here but are not among the types of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-universe"></emu-xref>, and `undefined` is not admitted in type position by <emu-xref href="#sec-type-expressions"></emu-xref>, which reaches `null` only through |PredefinedType|. The design nonetheless writes `undefined` as a type, since the reject type of a typed promise is `undefined` by convention when the promise never rejects. The type universe should name both, and the grammar should admit `undefined`.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-membership">
      <h1>Type Membership</h1>

      <emu-clause id="sec-isoftype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsOfType (
            _value_: an ECMAScript language value,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): either a normal completion containing a Boolean or a throw completion
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _value_ is a value of the type _t_. It may call user code, since deciding a structural type reads the value's properties.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return *true*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~void~, return *false*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
            1. For each element _m_ of _t_.[[Members]], do
              1. If ? IsOfType(_value_, _m_) is *true*, return *true*.
            1. Return *false*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~intersection~, then
            1. For each element _m_ of _t_.[[Members]], do
              1. If ? IsOfType(_value_, _m_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~literal~, return SameValue(_value_, _t_.[[Value]]).
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~object~, then
            1. If _value_ is not an Object, return *false*.
            1. For each Property Type Record _p_ of _t_.[[Properties]], do
              1. Let _present_ be ? HasProperty(_value_, _p_'s key).
              1. If _present_ is *false*, then
                1. If _p_ is not optional, return *false*.
              1. Else,
                1. Let _pv_ be ? Get(_value_, _p_'s key).
                1. If ? IsOfType(_pv_, _p_'s type) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return *true*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~array~ or _t_.[[Kind]] is ~tuple~, then
            1. If _value_ is not an Object, return *false*.
            1. Return ? the result of checking _value_'s length and elements against _t_ (<emu-xref href="#sec-array-membership"></emu-xref>).
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~function~, then
            1. If IsCallable(_value_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Return IsAssignable(RuntimeTypeOf(_value_), _t_).
          1. Return IsSubtype(RuntimeTypeOf(_value_), _t_, &laquo; &raquo;).
        </emu-alg>

        <emu-note>
          <p>Deciding a structural type reads the value's properties, so the check calls user code: a property backed by a getter runs it, which may throw, may have side effects, and may return a different value each time it is read. A check is therefore not a passive observation, and this is why the operation returns a completion. A getter that returns a value of the required type once and a different value afterwards defeats the check, which is the same aliasing exposure noted below. Whether a boundary check should read through accessors at all, or inspect only own data properties, remains open; reading them is assumed here because a property's type is a claim about what the property yields.</p>
          <p>The final step is the general case: the value's runtime type is compared against the target with the subtype relation of <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>, so the runtime test and the static one agree by construction. The earlier steps exist because a structural type cannot be decided by comparing two Type Records: an ordinary Object's runtime type is a description of the properties it happens to have, and the question is whether it has the ones the target requires.</p>
        </emu-note>

        <emu-note>
          <p>The ~function~ case is checked shallowly and is unsound, and this is the one place where the specification knowingly permits a type violation to go unreported. A function's signature cannot be verified without calling it, so the check confirms only that the value is callable and that the signature it declares is assignable to the target, which admits `any`. An untyped function reaching a `(uint8) =&gt; uint8` position therefore passes, and if it returns a String the caller receives one where its static type promised a `uint8`.</p>
          <p>This is the higher-order problem every gradual type system meets, and the design does not address it. The available answers are the known ones. The value can be wrapped so that each call checks its arguments and its result, which is sound and is what a contract system does, at the cost of an allocation per boundary crossing, a change to object identity, and a blame mechanism to say which side broke the contract. The check can stay shallow and the unsoundness be accepted, as an optional type system does, at the cost of the guarantee. Or a check can be inserted at each call through a binding whose runtime signature has an `any` where its static type does not, which is a wrapper by another name but pays only where the imprecision is. This clause specifies the shallow check so that the rest of the system is defined, and records that the choice is open. It bears on the proposal's central claim, since a type the engine cannot rely on is a type the engine cannot optimize against.</p>
          <p>The ~object~ case is checked at the boundary but not afterwards, and has the same shape of problem. A plain Object's properties are untyped unless declared with the `{ (a: uint8): 1 }` form of the object typing section, so an aliased write through an untyped reference can invalidate a check that has already passed. <emu-xref href="#sec-object-types-semantics"></emu-xref> settles whether a boundary imposes the target's property types on the object it accepts: it does not.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-the-boundary-check">
      <h1>The Boundary Check</h1>
      <p>At a boundary where a value of the `any` type reaches a position of a known type, the value is checked and, if it is a numeric value that the target can represent exactly, converted. A value the target cannot represent raises an error.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-requiretype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          RequireType (
            _value_: an ECMAScript language value,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): either a normal completion containing an ECMAScript language value or a throw completion
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It enforces the type _t_ on _value_ at a boundary, returning the value of the type _t_ to be used.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If ? IsOfType(_value_, _t_) is *true*, return _value_.
          1. If _t_ is a numeric type and RuntimeTypeOf(_value_) is a numeric type, then
            1. Let _r_ be the result of converting _value_ to _t_ by <emu-xref href="#table-numeric-conversions"></emu-xref>, except that a conversion that would wrap, truncate toward zero, or round a finite value to an infinity instead yields ~unrepresentable~.
            1. If _r_ is ~unrepresentable~, throw a *RangeError* exception.
            1. Return _r_.
          1. Throw a *TypeError* exception.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <p>The three ways a numeric value may fail to fit a type are distinguished, and each is treated according to what the program said.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-out-of-range-treatment" caption="Treatment of a Value That Does Not Fit">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>The program writes</th><th>Example</th><th>Treatment</th><th>Because</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>A literal in a typed position</td><td>`let u: uint8 = 300;`</td><td>An Early Error. The source text does not compile.</td><td>A literal that does not fit its type is a mistake, and it is visible in the source text.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>An explicit conversion</td><td>`uint8(300)`</td><td>The value wraps, to 44.</td><td>A cast is an instruction to discard information. The program asked.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A value of the `any` type at a typed boundary</td><td>`let u: uint8 = anyValue;`</td><td>A *RangeError* at run time.</td><td>Nothing in the source text says to discard information, and the value is not known until it arrives.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The boundary converts rather than merely checking, which is what makes untyped data usable: a Number parsed from JSON reaching a `uint8` field is a Number, not a `uint8`, and a check that demanded it already be a `uint8` would reject every value that ever crossed the boundary. Converting only where the target can represent the value exactly, and raising a *RangeError* otherwise, keeps the loss from being silent. This is the same distinction the checked arithmetic of `Math.addChecked` draws against the wrapping of `+`.</p>
        <p>The rule above permits a float target to round, since it treats only wrapping, truncation, and overflow to an infinity as unrepresentable, so a Number 0.1 reaching a `float32` boundary becomes the nearest `float32`. The alternative, demanding exactness, would reject almost every float that crossed a boundary and is not usable. This matches the treatment of a literal, which also rounds into a float and errors only outside the range, and it is recorded here because it is a choice rather than a consequence.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-check-insertion">
      <h1>Where Checks Are Inserted</h1>
      <p>A check is inserted where a value whose static type is `any` reaches a position whose type is not, and nowhere else. <emu-xref href="#table-check-sites"></emu-xref> lists the positions.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-check-sites" caption="Boundaries">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Position</th><th>Check</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>The initializer or assigned value of a binding with a declared type _t_</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>An argument passed to a parameter of declared type _t_</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>The operand of a `return` in a function with a declared return type _t_</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A value stored to a property or field of declared type _t_</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A value stored to an element of an array of element type _t_</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A value read from a position of the `any` type into an operator whose operands are typed</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_) for the operand type _t_ the operator requires</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A value crossing into a typed position through reflection, including `Reflect.set` and `Reflect.defineProperty`</td><td>RequireType(_value_, _t_)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The list is the same list of boundaries at which a user-defined conversion is consulted (<emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-conversions"></emu-xref>) and at which the metadata protocol of the primitive metadata extension applies, and at which a `where` clause that cannot be decided statically is evaluated. This is not a coincidence: a boundary is where a value acquires a type it did not have, and every mechanism that has something to say about that acquisition says it there.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-check-elision">
      <h1>Elision of Checks</h1>
      <p>A check is required only where the static types do not already establish the result. It is not inserted, and an implementation need not perform one, in the following circumstances.</p>

      <ul>
        <li>The static type of the value is not `any` and is assignable to the target. The result is established statically, and any violation was an Early Error.</li>
        <li>The target is the `any` type. Every value is a value of it.</li>
        <li>The value's static type and the target are the same type.</li>
        <li>The index of a read or write of a fixed-length `[N].&lt;T&gt;` is known to be below _N_, because _N_ is a compile-time constant and the index is a value generic, a `where`-constrained parameter, or the counter of a `for` over a range with that bound. The bound is proven statically and no check is performed.</li>
      </ul>

      <emu-note>
        <p>In a fully typed program every check above is elided, and what remains at the boundaries of a partly typed one reduces to a tag test on a sealed typed class. This is the property the proposal's premise rests on: a check the engine can discharge statically is not a cost, and the type is available to the engine as a fact rather than a hint. A program that is entirely untyped inserts no checks either, since it has no typed positions. The cost falls where the boundary is, in proportion to how mixed the program is.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-typed-storage">
      <h1>Typed Storage</h1>
      <p>A class in which at least one public or private field is typed is automatically sealed, as if PreventExtensions had been performed on each of its instances, and its prototype is frozen. A field may be written, since a field's type is what constrains it, but a property may not be added or removed, and the prototype may not be modified.</p>

      <p>A store to a typed field or a typed element checks the value against the field's or element's declared type, by <emu-xref href="#table-check-sites"></emu-xref>. Deleting a typed field, a typed element, or a member required by an implemented interface throws a *TypeError* exception.</p>

      <p>A class whose fields are typed may opt out with the `dynamic` modifier, which leaves it unsealed. Such a class cannot be used for sequential data and cannot be a value type in a typed array.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Sealing is what makes a typed field's type a fact about the layout rather than a claim about the initializer. Without it a typed class would be a class whose fields happen to have been assigned values of the right type so far, which is not something an engine can lay out contiguously or an offset can be computed from. The memory layout extension depends on this, and it is the reason sealing is automatic rather than requested: a field's type and a reallocatable object are not compatible, so the type implies the seal.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-instanceof-for-type-objects">
      <h1>The instanceof Operator</h1>
      <p>A Type Object has a %Symbol.hasInstance% method. When called with argument _v_, it returns ? IsOfType(_v_, the Type Object's [[TypeRecord]]).</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`instanceof` therefore extends to every type of this proposal through the protocol the language already has, and needs no new operator. `a instanceof uint8` is *true* for a `uint8` binding and `a instanceof uint16` is *false*, a fixed-length array is an instance of the corresponding dynamic-length array type, and a class is unaffected, since a class's type object is its constructor and the prototype chain semantics apply as they do today. A successful check narrows the static type in the branch it guards, which <emu-xref href="#sec-narrowing"></emu-xref> specifies.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-declarations">
    <h1>Declarations</h1>
    <p>This clause gives meaning to the annotations the grammar attached to bindings in <emu-xref href="#sec-type-annotations"></emu-xref>. It specifies what a typed binding holds before it is assigned, what a typed initializer infers, what an assignment to a typed binding does, the declaration that names a type, and the narrowing by which a test refines the type of a binding in the branch it guards.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-alias-declarations">
      <h1>Type Alias Declarations</h1>
      <p>A type alias declaration names a type. It is added to the declaration forms.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        Declaration[Yield, Await] :
          HoistableDeclaration[?Yield, ?Await, ~Default]
          ClassDeclaration[?Yield, ?Await, ~Default]
          LexicalDeclaration[+In, ?Yield, ?Await]
          <ins>TypeAliasDeclaration[?Yield, ?Await]</ins>

        <ins>TypeAliasDeclaration[Yield, Await] :
          `type` [no LineTerminator here] BindingIdentifier[?Yield, ?Await] TypeParameters[?Yield, ?Await]? `=` Type[?Yield, ?Await] `;`</ins>
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>A type alias declaration with no |TypeParameters| creates an immutable binding for its |BindingIdentifier|, initialized to GetTypeObject of the Type Record its |Type| denotes. The name is therefore usable in expression position, where it evaluates to that Type Object, and in type position, where it denotes the type. A declaration with |TypeParameters| creates no binding and is usable only in type position, since a generic alias denotes a type for each list of arguments rather than one type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`type Point = { x: float32, y: float32 };` is therefore close to a `const` whose value is a type object, and the two spellings agree: `Point === type { x: float32, y: float32 }` is *true*, because Type Objects are interned (<emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref>). What the declaration adds over the `const` is that the name is also usable where a type is expected. An alias is transparent: it introduces no new type, so `Point` and its expansion are the same type and are mutually assignable, and a nominal type is created only by a class, an interface, or an enum.</p>

      <p>An alias may refer to itself, directly or through other aliases, provided every cycle passes through a position that holds a reference rather than an inline layout: a member written `T | null`, the element of a dynamic array, or a field of a sealed class. It is a type error if a cycle never does, since the type would demand an infinite inline layout, which is the same rule <emu-xref href="#sec-typed-classes"></emu-xref> applies to a value type class containing itself. The fixpoint of <emu-xref href="#sec-evaluatebuildercall"></emu-xref> validates a computed cycle by this rule.</p>
        <p>The `[no LineTerminator here]` restriction is what keeps `type` a contextual keyword. `type` followed by a line terminator and then an identifier is two statements today, an expression statement naming `type` and another naming the identifier, and it continues to be. This is the same device the design relies on throughout, and it is why `type X = 1;` on one line is unambiguous: it is a syntax error today.</p>
        <p>Whether a generic alias may be exported, and how `export type Point = ...` interacts with the module's binding namespace, is left to the modules clause. A generic alias creating no binding is a decision worth revisiting: it means `Grown` in `type Grown&lt;T&gt; = [...Row, T];` cannot be reflected on, while a non-generic alias can be.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-typed-bindings">
      <h1>Typed Bindings</h1>
      <p>`var`, `let`, and `const` accept the same annotations. A binding declared with a |TypeAnnotation| has the annotated type; a binding declared without one has the `any` type. The type of a binding is fixed at its declaration and does not change with what is assigned to it.</p>

      <p>A binding declared with a type and an |Initializer| is initialized to the value of the initializer, checked against the declared type by the rules of <emu-xref href="#sec-conversions"></emu-xref>: the check is static where the initializer's type is known, and is RequireType where the initializer has the `any` type. A binding declared with a type and no |Initializer| is initialized to the default value of that type (<emu-xref href="#sec-default-values"></emu-xref>) rather than to *undefined*.</p>

      <p>A `const` declaration without an |Initializer| remains a Syntax Error, whether or not the binding carries a |TypeAnnotation|.</p>

      <p>Assignment to a binding of declared type _t_ checks the assigned value against _t_ by the same rules. The temporal dead zone is unchanged: a `let` or `const` binding is uninitialized until its declaration is evaluated, and accessing it before then is a *ReferenceError*. The default value applies at the declaration, not before it.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>That a typed binding takes its type's default rather than *undefined* is the point at which a type stops being a claim about a program and becomes a fact about storage. `let a: uint32;` holds a `uint32`, so every read of it yields a `uint32` and the engine may lay it out as four bytes; were it *undefined* until assigned, its type would be `uint32 | undefined` in all but name, and the layout would have to carry a bit saying which. This is the same reason a typed field takes its type's default, and the two rules are one rule.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-default-values">
      <h1>Default Values</h1>

      <emu-clause id="sec-defaultvalueof" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          DefaultValueOf (
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): either a value of the type _t_ or ~none~
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the value a binding or field of the type _t_ holds before it is assigned, or ~none~ if _t_ has no default.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return *undefined*.
          1. If _t_ is a numeric type, return the value of _t_ representing 0.
          1. If _t_ is the String type, return the empty String.
          1. If _t_ is the Boolean type, return *false*.
          1. If _t_ is the type named *"undefined"*, return *undefined*.
          1. If _t_ is the type named *"null"*, return *null*.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
            1. If _t_.[[Members]] contains the type named *"null"*, return *null*.
            1. If _t_.[[Members]] contains the type named *"undefined"*, return *undefined*.
            1. Return ~none~.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~array~, then
            1. If _t_.[[Extent]] is ~dynamic~, return a new empty array of the type _t_.
            1. Let _d_ be DefaultValueOf(_t_.[[Element]]).
            1. If _d_ is ~none~, return ~none~.
            1. Return a new array of the type _t_ whose _t_.[[Extent]] elements are each _d_.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~tuple~, then
            1. For each element _e_ of _t_.[[Elements]], do
              1. If _e_.[[Rest]] is *false* and _e_.[[Initial]] is ~none~ and DefaultValueOf(_e_.[[Type]]) is ~none~, return ~none~.
            1. Return a new tuple of the type _t_ whose elements are, for each element of _t_.[[Elements]] whose [[Rest]] is *false* and in order, its [[Initial]] where that is not ~none~ and the default value of its [[Type]] otherwise.
          1. If _t_.[[Kind]] is ~nominal~ and _t_ denotes a value type class, return the instance of _t_ each of whose fields holds the default of the field's type, or ~none~ if any field's type has no default.
          1. Return ~none~.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <p>It is a type error to declare a binding or a field with a type _t_ and no initializer when DefaultValueOf(_t_) is ~none~.</p>

      <p>Every default above is a zero: the numeric zero, the empty String, *false*, *null*, and an array or an aggregate whose storage is zero-filled. Zero-filling is part of the semantics and not an optimization a program may opt out of, and no form of this proposal allocates without it.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The reason is security rather than convenience. An allocation that exposed the bytes of a previously freed one would leak whatever had been there: another script's data, a former secret, or a heap pointer that defeats address space layout randomization. A fresh page from the operating system is already zero, so the fill costs nothing on a large new allocation, and reused memory must be cleared regardless, so there is nothing to gain by exposing it. The one pattern an uninitialized form would serve, allocate and then fill from input, is served by placement `new` over an existing buffer and by array views.</p>
        <p>A type with no default is one for which no zero is meaningful, and the operation reports that rather than inventing one. A union of two non-nullable types is the ordinary case: `let x: uint8 | string;` has two candidate zeros and no reason to prefer either, so it requires an initializer. `symbol`, `object`, a function type, and a class whose construction must run are the others.</p>
        <p>The design states the defaults for the numeric, SIMD, String, Boolean, nullable, and array types and does not reach the rest, so the boundaries above are supplied here and need review. Three deserve attention. A `bigint` is given the zero `0n` on the same reasoning as the other numeric types. A tuple defaults element-wise, which follows from a tuple of value types being laid out contiguously, but a tuple with a defaulted trailing position already has an initializer for that position, which <emu-xref href="#sec-array-defaults-and-stores"></emu-xref> reconciles. A value type class defaults field-wise, which is what makes `let d: [10].&lt;A&gt;;` hold ten zero-filled instances as the memory layout extension requires, but it means a class can be brought into existence without its constructor running, which <emu-xref href="#sec-typed-classes"></emu-xref> endorses.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-typed-initializers-semantics">
      <h1>Typed Initializers</h1>
      <p>A binding declared with a |TypedInitializer| takes the type of its initializer rather than the `any` type. Its declared type is the Static Type of the |AssignmentExpression|, and it is initialized to that expression's value.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`let a := new MyType();` declares `a` of type `MyType`, where `let a = new MyType();` would declare it of the `any` type. The two spellings differ in what may be assigned afterwards, not in what is stored: the first rejects `a = 5`, the second permits it. `:=` therefore removes the redundancy of `let a: MyType = new MyType();` without introducing inference anywhere the program did not ask for it, which is why it is a distinct operator rather than a rule that an initialized binding infers its type. An unannotated binding remaining `any` is what keeps an untyped program untyped.</p>
        <p>It is a type error if the Static Type of the initializer is the `any` type, since `let a := f();` where `f` is untyped would declare a binding of the `any` type through a syntax that asks for a type.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-narrowing">
      <h1>Narrowing</h1>
      <p>A test that establishes something about a value's type refines the Static Type of that value in the branch the test guards. The Static Type of a reference to a binding at a given point is its declared type refined by the narrowing facts that hold there.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-narrowing-forms" caption="Narrowing Forms">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Form</th><th>Where true</th><th>Where false</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>`v instanceof T`</td><td>NarrowTo(_s_, _T_)</td><td>NarrowFrom(_s_, _T_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`#f in v`, a brand check</td><td>NarrowTo(_s_, the class declaring `#f`)</td><td>NarrowFrom(_s_, the class declaring `#f`)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`v is T`, the structural test of the dependent record types extension</td><td>NarrowTo(_s_, _T_)</td><td>NarrowFrom(_s_, _T_)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`typeof v === ` a String literal _k_</td><td>NarrowTo(_s_, the union of the types whose `typeof` is _k_)</td><td>NarrowFrom(_s_, that union)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`v == null` or `v != null`, and the nullish operators `??`, `??=`, and `?.`</td><td>The nullish branch: NarrowTo(_s_, `null | undefined`)</td><td>The present branch: NarrowFrom(_s_, `null | undefined`)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>A `switch` on a value of an enum type or a sealed class hierarchy</td><td>In each case, NarrowTo(_s_, the case's type)</td><td>In the default, _s_ with every case's type removed</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <p>_s_ above is the Static Type of `v` where the test occurs. A narrowing fact holds in any position the test governs, not only in the body of an `if`: the two branches of a conditional expression are narrowed by its condition, the right operand of `&amp;&amp;` is narrowed by the truth of its left operand, and the right operand of `||` by the falsity of its left. A fact about a binding holds until the binding is assigned a value whose type is not within the narrowed type.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-narrowto" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          NarrowTo (
            _s_: a Type Record,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): either a Type Record or ~empty~
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the type of a value known to be of the type _s_ and also of the type _t_, or ~empty~ if no value can be of both.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~any~, return _t_.
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
            1. Let _kept_ be a new empty List.
            1. For each element _m_ of _s_.[[Members]], do
              1. If IsSubtype(_m_, _t_, &laquo; &raquo;) is *true*, append _m_ to _kept_.
              1. Else if IsSubtype(_t_, _m_, &laquo; &raquo;) is *true*, append _t_ to _kept_.
            1. If _kept_ is empty, return ~empty~.
            1. Return CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: _kept_ }).
          1. If IsSubtype(_s_, _t_, &laquo; &raquo;) is *true*, return _s_.
          1. If IsSubtype(_t_, _s_, &laquo; &raquo;) is *true*, return _t_.
          1. If _s_ and _t_ have no common values, return ~empty~.
          1. Return CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~intersection~, [[Members]]: &laquo; _s_, _t_ &raquo; }).
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Two distinct ~primitive~ types have no common values, since each value belongs to exactly one of them (<emu-xref href="#sec-value-types"></emu-xref>), and neither does a ~primitive~ type share values with an ~object~ or ~function~ type. Two ~object~ types, or two ~nominal~ types that are interfaces, may have common values, since a class may satisfy both, so an intersection of those is inhabited and is returned. This is the step that yields ~empty~ for `d ?? 5` where `d` is a `uint8`: the narrowed type would be the intersection of `uint8` and `null | undefined`, which has no values.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-narrowfrom" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          NarrowFrom (
            _s_: a Type Record,
            _t_: a Type Record,
          ): either a Type Record or ~empty~
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns the type of a value known to be of the type _s_ and not of the type _t_, or ~empty~ if there is no such value.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _s_.[[Kind]] is ~union~, then
            1. Let _kept_ be a new empty List.
            1. For each element _m_ of _s_.[[Members]], do
              1. If IsSubtype(_m_, _t_, &laquo; &raquo;) is *false*, append _m_ to _kept_.
            1. If _kept_ is empty, return ~empty~.
            1. Return CanonicalizeType(the Type Record { [[Kind]]: ~union~, [[Members]]: _kept_ }).
          1. If IsSubtype(_s_, _t_, &laquo; &raquo;) is *true*, return ~empty~.
          1. Return _s_.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <p>It is a type error to apply a narrowing form where the test can never succeed or can never fail, since the branch it guards is then dead code the program did not intend. These are the branches for which NarrowTo or NarrowFrom returns ~empty~. The sentinel is deliberately not the `never` type (<emu-xref href="#sec-never-type"></emu-xref>): a test that cannot succeed is reported as a mistake rather than narrowed to the type with no values, because a branch the program wrote and can never take is dead code and not a computation.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>This is why `d ?? 5` is rejected where `d` is a `uint8`: the left operand can never be nullish, so NarrowTo of `uint8` and `null | undefined` keeps no member and the test is a mistake rather than silent dead code. The same rule rejects `a instanceof string` where `a` is a `uint8`.</p>
        <p>Narrowing on `typeof` is weaker here than in a type system layered over the language, and deliberately so, because `typeof` is unchanged: it reports *"number"* for every numeric type, so `typeof v === "number"` narrows `uint8 | string` to `uint8` but cannot separate `uint8` from `uint16`, and reports *"object"* for the SIMD, rational, and complex types. `Reflect.typeOf` and `instanceof` are what distinguish those, and `instanceof` is the form that narrows. A program discriminating a union of numeric types therefore writes `instanceof`, not `typeof`.</p>
        <p>Narrowing a binding rather than an expression is sound here only because a narrowed binding is invalidated by an assignment that leaves the narrowed type, which the last sentence above states. The design's `a ??= 5;` narrowing `a` to `uint8` "until a nullable reassignment" is that rule. It is worth noting what this clause does not give: a narrowing of a property or an element, `if (o.f instanceof T)`, is not stated by the design and is not specified here, and it cannot be sound without knowing that `o.f` is not reassigned in between, which for a sealed typed class of a `readonly` field is knowable and otherwise is not. <emu-xref href="#sec-object-types-semantics"></emu-xref> settles it.</p>
        <p>The `switch` row covers the exhaustiveness the design reserves to enums and sealed classes. A union of literal types deliberately does not drive exhaustiveness, so it narrows in each case but its `default` is not proven unreachable.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-operators">
    <h1>Operators</h1>
    <p>This clause specifies what an operator does when its operands are typed. Little new machinery is required, because the specification already has the mechanism: when BigInt was introduced, the operators were generalized from one numeric type to two, and an operator now reduces its operands to numeric values, rejects a pair whose types differ, and dispatches to an abstract operation belonging to the type. This proposal adds numeric types to that mechanism. It does not add a second one.</p>

    <emu-note>
      <p>The principle the design states is that typed code changes what a program checks and what its values can represent, and does not change what an operator means. Every rule below follows from it. Where an operator's result is forced by the type rather than chosen, as an integer quotient is, the type decides; everywhere else the operator means what it means today.</p>
    </emu-note>

    <emu-clause id="sec-operator-dispatch">
      <h1>Dispatch</h1>
      <p>ToNumeric is revised so that a value of a numeric type of this proposal reaches an operator as itself rather than as a Number.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-tonumeric-revised" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          ToNumeric (
            _value_: an ECMAScript language value,
          ): either a normal completion containing either a Number, a BigInt, or a value of a numeric type of this proposal, or a throw completion
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It returns _value_ converted to a numeric value, preserving the numeric type it already has.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. Let _primValue_ be ? ToPrimitive(_value_, ~number~).
          1. <ins>If _primValue_ is a value of a numeric type of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-universe"></emu-xref>, return _primValue_.</ins>
          1. If _primValue_ is a BigInt, return _primValue_.
          1. Return ? ToNumber(_primValue_).
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <p>The remaining machinery is unchanged and generalizes as written. In <emu-xref href="#sec-applystringornumericbinaryoperator"></emu-xref>, the step that throws a *TypeError* when the two operands are not of the same numeric type applies to every numeric type, and the table associating an operator with an abstract operation is read as associating it with _T_::op for the numeric type _T_ of the operands. The operations are those of <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>This is the whole of the dispatch. `1n + 1` already throws a *TypeError* today because the two operands are of different numeric types and neither converts to the other, and `uint8(1) + uint16(1)` throws for exactly the same reason, by the same step, with no rule specific to it. The shape the committee arrived at for BigInt, an operator that dispatches on the numeric type of its operands and refuses to mix them, is the shape this proposal needs, which is why adding sixteen numeric types costs one inserted step.</p>
        <p>ToNumber is not reached for a typed operand and so is never the vehicle for an implicit conversion, which is what <emu-xref href="#sec-existing-abstract-conversion-operations"></emu-xref> anticipated. ToNumber keeps its meaning for a value of the `any` type, whose numeric type is not known statically: the operand arrives as whatever it is, and the same steps apply to it dynamically.</p>
        <p>The string behaviour of `+` is unchanged and applies before any of this: if either operand is a String after ToPrimitive, the result is the concatenation. `uint8(1) + "x"` is therefore *"1x"*. This is not an implicit conversion between value types in the sense <emu-xref href="#sec-the-conversion-rule"></emu-xref> forbids, since no `uint8` becomes a value of another numeric type; it is the meaning `+` has always had, and changing it for typed operands would violate the principle above.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-arithmetic-never-promotes">
      <h1>Arithmetic Never Promotes</h1>
      <p>Two operands of the same value type produce a result of that type. Two operands of different value types are a type error, since neither is assignable to the other. Where one operand is a literal it takes the type of the other (<emu-xref href="#sec-literal-propagation"></emu-xref>), so a literal never forces a conversion.</p>

      <p>It is a type error if the Static Types of the operands of an arithmetic, bitwise, shift, or relational operator are numeric types that are not the same type. Where either operand has the `any` type the check is deferred, and the *TypeError* of <emu-xref href="#sec-operator-dispatch"></emu-xref> is thrown at run time if the types then differ.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`float32` arithmetic is `float32` arithmetic: `x * x` for a `float32` `x` is computed in `float32` and rounds once, rather than widening to `float64` and rounding twice. C promotes `float` to `double` in many contexts, so the same source can produce different results depending on where a value is used, and the reproducibility this proposal offers across engines depends on refusing that.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-which-operations-each-family-defines">
      <h1>The Operations Each Family Defines</h1>
      <p>A numeric type defines the operations of <emu-xref href="#table-family-operations"></emu-xref>. An operator whose operation the operand's type does not define is a type error.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-family-operations" caption="Operations by Family">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Family</th><th>Defines</th><th>Does not define</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>integer</td><td>Every operation of <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal"></emu-xref>.</td><td>None.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>binary floating-point, and the Number type</td><td>unaryMinus, exponentiate, multiply, divide, remainder, add, subtract, lessThan, equal, sameValue, sameValueZero, toString.</td><td>For a binary floating-point type of this proposal: bitwiseNOT, the shifts, and the bitwise operations, since each would require converting the operand to an integer type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>decimal floating-point</td><td>unaryMinus, exponentiate, multiply, divide, remainder, add, subtract, lessThan, equal, sameValue, sameValueZero, toString.</td><td>bitwiseNOT, the shifts, and the bitwise operations.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>rational</td><td>unaryMinus, multiply, divide, add, subtract, lessThan, equal, sameValue, sameValueZero, toString.</td><td>bitwiseNOT, the shifts, the bitwise operations, and remainder. exponentiate is defined only for an integer exponent.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>complex</td><td>unaryMinus, exponentiate, multiply, divide, add, subtract, equal, sameValue, sameValueZero, toString.</td><td>lessThan, since the complex numbers are not ordered; remainder; and the bitwise and shift operations.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>vector</td><td>unaryMinus, multiply, divide, add, subtract, equal, sameValue, sameValueZero, toString, applied lane-wise; and the bitwise and shift operations where the lane type is an integer type.</td><td>lessThan, whose result for a vector is a vector of lane results rather than a Boolean. The SIMD extension declares the comparison operators on the vector types instead, overloaded on their return type, so they dispatch by <emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-operators"></emu-xref> rather than through the protocol.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The Number type continues to define the bitwise and shift operations, which convert their operand with ToInt32 as they do today, and no existing program changes. A `float32` does not, because the same conversion applied to it would be an implicit conversion between two value types: `~x` for a `float32` `x` is a type error rather than a silent trip through `int32`. This is the one place where an operator that works on a Number does not work on the corresponding typed value, and it follows from the conversion rule rather than from a decision about bitwise operators.</p>
        <p>The table is the answer to the three cases <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal"></emu-xref> left open. Two of them are absences, complex having no order and a rational having no remainder. The third, a vector comparison returning a vector, is not an absence but a signature the protocol cannot express, since lessThan is required to return a Boolean. Rather than widening the protocol for one family, the vector comparisons are declared operators, which is a path the specification already provides and which admits the return-type overloading they need (<emu-xref href="#sec-overloading-on-return-type"></emu-xref>).</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-integer-operations">
      <h1>Integer Operations</h1>
      <p>For an integer type _T_ of width _N_, each operation computes the exact mathematical result and then reduces it to a value of _T_ as <emu-xref href="#table-numeric-conversions"></emu-xref> specifies for an integer target: the result is taken modulo 2**_N_ and interpreted as a value of _T_. Overflow therefore wraps, in two's complement for a signed type, and discards the bits that do not fit.</p>

      <p>_T_::divide returns the exact quotient truncated toward zero. _T_::remainder returns the remainder whose sign follows the dividend, unchanged in meaning from the Number type. If the divisor is zero, both throw a *RangeError* exception.</p>

      <p>It is a type error if the divisor of `/` or `%` is a literal zero and the operands are of an integer type of this proposal.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Truncating toward zero and taking the remainder's sign from the dividend are one decision rather than two, because the identity `(a / b) * b + a % b = a` holds only when the quotient and the remainder round the same way. Truncated division pairs with a dividend-signed remainder and floored division with a divisor-signed one; mixing them produces an arithmetic that does not add back up whenever the dividend is negative and the remainder is not zero, which is two of the four sign combinations. The floored pair is available under its own name rather than by redefining the operators, as `Math.divFloor` and `Math.mod` in <emu-xref href="#sec-floored-division"></emu-xref>.</p>
        <p>That an integer quotient truncates is not a choice. An `int32` has nowhere to put 1.5, so the result type decides the answer, and this is the one operator whose meaning the type changes. A floored `%` would be a choice, since both answers fit the type, which is why the operator keeps the meaning it has for a Number.</p>
        <p>Division by zero throws because an integer type has no infinity and no NaN, so there is nothing to return. A float is unaffected and keeps the answer it has today: `float32(1) / 0` is an infinity and `float32(1) % 0` is a NaN, because a float has somewhere to put them.</p>
        <p>The literal-zero rule matches the treatment of a literal that does not fit its type (<emu-xref href="#table-out-of-range-treatment"></emu-xref>): it is a mistake visible in the source text, so it does not compile, while a divisor whose value is not known until run time raises a *RangeError* there. It deliberately does not extend to `bigint`, where `1n / 0n` continues to throw a *RangeError* exception at run time: that expression is legal today, and rejecting it earlier would break an existing program. The asymmetry is a compatibility constraint rather than a design view, and it is worth stating in the design document, which does not currently note that the rule stops at the new types.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-unary-operators-for-typed-values">
      <h1>Unary Operators</h1>
      <p>Unary `-` applies _T_::unaryMinus for the numeric type _T_ of its operand. For an unsigned integer type of width _N_, the result is 2**_N_ minus the operand, modulo 2**_N_, so unary minus on an unsigned value wraps rather than raising an error.</p>

      <p>Unary `+` returns its operand unchanged when the operand is a value of a numeric type of this proposal. It continues to throw a *TypeError* for a BigInt, and continues to apply ToNumber otherwise.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Unary minus on an unsigned value is defined rather than rejected because the alternative is worse: an unsigned type is a bit pattern as much as a count, and `-x` on it is the two's complement negation the hardware computes. Casting to the signed type first is usually clearer, and a program that wants the error uses the checked form.</p>
        <p>Unary `+` is a decision, and it is recorded here because it splits from BigInt. `+x` throws for a BigInt because `+x` is the idiom for coercing to a Number, and returning a BigInt from it would silently defeat that idiom. The same argument applies to a `uint8`, and would say `+x` should throw for every type this proposal adds. Against it: `operator+()` is an overloadable unary operator on a class in the design, so unary `+` already means more than ToNumber, and an earlier clause of this specification states that `+a` on a `uint8` is a `uint8`. This clause follows the design. If the committee prefers consistency with BigInt, the change is to this step alone, and it would make `+x` a *TypeError* for every numeric type of this proposal.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-equality-and-comparison">
      <h1>Equality and Comparison</h1>
      <p>`===` and `!==` are not overloadable and retain their identity semantics. What identity means follows from the type. The identity of a reference type is the reference, so two distinct objects are never `===`. The identity of a value type is its value, as it already is for a `uint8` and a String, so two instances of a value type class are `===` exactly when their fields are, compared field by field.</p>

      <p>`==` between two values of the same numeric type applies _T_::equal. Between two values of different numeric types it is *false* rather than a type error, as it is today between a Number and a BigInt of unequal value, and IsLooselyEqual continues to compare their mathematical values where both are numeric. A decimal compares by numerical value, so a value with trailing zeros equals one without them (<emu-xref href="#sec-decimal-floating-point-types"></emu-xref>).</p>

      <p>The relational operators apply _T_::lessThan through IsLessThan, unchanged.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>That `===` compares a value type class field by field rather than by reference is what makes a value type a value: two `Vector2` instances holding the same coordinates are the same value, and a `Map` keyed on them has one entry. This is the existing rule for a `uint8` and a String applied to an aggregate, not a new one.</p>
        <p>`==` returning *false* across numeric types rather than throwing is the existing treatment of a Number against a BigInt, and it is deliberately not aligned with the arithmetic operators, which do throw. The design does not state a rule for `==` between two typed values, so this follows the existing behaviour, but it is a place where the specification and the design should be reconciled: a proposal that rejects `uint8(1) + uint16(1)` at compile time and quietly answers `uint8(1) == uint16(1)` with a comparison of mathematical values is defensible, since equality asks a question rather than producing a value of some type, but it should be a stated position rather than an inherited one.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-user-defined-operators">
      <h1>User-Defined Operators</h1>
      <p>A class may declare an operator, in which case the receiver is the left operand and the declaration's parameter is the right. Where an operator's operands are of a type that declares it, the declaration is applied in place of the steps above. The overloadable operators are the arithmetic, bitwise, shift, relational, and logical operators, their compound assignment forms, the increment and decrement operators in prefix and postfix form, the unary operators, the index accessors, and the conversion operator of <emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-conversions"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <p>`===` and `!==` are not overloadable. An operator that the operand's type already defines through <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal"></emu-xref> may not be redeclared for that type, so a program cannot redefine `uint8` addition. An operator a built-in type does not define may be declared for it, which is how the SIMD extension gives the vector types their comparisons and how the primitive metadata extension declares operators on a parameterized primitive.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Resolution among several declarations of one operator is overload resolution on the operand types, specified in <emu-xref href="#sec-overload-resolution"></emu-xref>. The operator overloading extension works the rules through a case where the receiver is not the left operand, a scalar multiplying a vector, and states what an engine must guarantee for the result to compile as well as the equivalent C++ would.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-functions">
    <h1>Functions and Overloading</h1>
    <p>This clause defines the structure of a function type, the identity and subtyping of one, and the resolution of a call among several signatures declared for one name.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-signature-records">
      <h1>Signature Records</h1>
      <p>A <dfn id="signature-record">Signature Record</dfn> describes one callable signature. It has the fields of <emu-xref href="#table-signature-record"></emu-xref>. A ~function~ Type Record's [[Signatures]] is a List of them, with more than one element when the function is overloaded.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-signature-record" caption="Signature Record Fields">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Value</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>[[Parameters]]</td><td>a List of Parameter Records</td><td>The parameters, in order.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>[[Return]]</td><td>a Type Record</td><td>The declared return type, or the `any` type where none is declared.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>[[ThisType]]</td><td>a Type Record or ~none~</td><td>The declared `this` type, or ~none~ where none is declared.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>[[TypeParameters]]</td><td>a List of Parse Nodes</td><td>The type parameters the signature declares, empty when it is not generic.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>[[Untyped]]</td><td>a Boolean</td><td>*true* when the signature declares no parameter type and no return type, in which case it is a catch-all.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <p>A <dfn id="parameter-record">Parameter Record</dfn> has a [[Name]] (a String), a [[Type]] (a Type Record), an [[Optional]] field (a Boolean, *true* when the parameter is marked `?` or has a default), a [[Rest]] field (a Boolean), an [[Initial]] field (an ECMAScript language value or ~none~, the declared default), and a [[Reference]] field (a Boolean). [[Reference]] is *true* exactly when [[Type]].[[Kind]] is ~reference~: the flag restates the type for convenience, and reflection reads the fact from the type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>A signature is identified by its parameter types and its return type, so two declarations of one name may differ in the return type alone (<emu-xref href="#sec-overloading-on-return-type"></emu-xref>). A parameter's name is carried because the design's named arguments select by it, and is not part of the signature's identity. A parameter's [[Initial]] and a signature's [[ThisType]] are part of the identity, compared by SameValue and as a type; the name remains the one non-canonical field. The rules that consume [[ThisType]], its contravariant place in subtyping and the contextual adoption of an expected `this` by a function literal, are parked with the design's declarative checker facts alongside declared narrowing (<emu-xref href="#table-extension-hooks"></emu-xref>).</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-function-type-identity-and-subtyping">
      <h1>Identity and Subtyping of Function Types</h1>
      <p>These operations complete the cases <emu-xref href="#sec-sametypewithassumptions"></emu-xref> and <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref> defer for the ~function~ kind.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-samefunctiontype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          SameFunctionType (
            _s_: a ~function~ Type Record,
            _t_: a ~function~ Type Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _s_ and _t_ are the same function type.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _s_.[[Signatures]] and _t_.[[Signatures]] do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
          1. For each integer _i_ such that 0 &le; _i_ and _i_ &lt; the number of elements of _s_.[[Signatures]], do
            1. Let _a_ be _s_.[[Signatures]][_i_].
            1. Let _b_ be _t_.[[Signatures]][_i_].
            1. If _a_.[[Parameters]] and _b_.[[Parameters]] do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
            1. For each integer _j_ such that 0 &le; _j_ and _j_ &lt; the number of elements of _a_.[[Parameters]], do
              1. Let _p_ be _a_.[[Parameters]][_j_].
              1. Let _q_ be _b_.[[Parameters]][_j_].
              1. If _p_.[[Optional]] is not _q_.[[Optional]], return *false*.
              1. If _p_.[[Rest]] is not _q_.[[Rest]], return *false*.
              1. If _p_.[[Reference]] is not _q_.[[Reference]], return *false*.
              1. If _p_.[[Initial]] is ~none~ or _q_.[[Initial]] is ~none~, then
                1. If _p_.[[Initial]] is not ~none~ or _q_.[[Initial]] is not ~none~, return *false*.
              1. Else if SameValue(_p_.[[Initial]], _q_.[[Initial]]) is *false*, then
                1. Return *false*.
              1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_p_.[[Type]], _q_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. If _a_.[[ThisType]] is ~none~ or _b_.[[ThisType]] is ~none~, then
              1. If _a_.[[ThisType]] is not ~none~ or _b_.[[ThisType]] is not ~none~, return *false*.
            1. Else if SameTypeWithAssumptions(_a_.[[ThisType]], _b_.[[ThisType]], _assumptions_) is *false*, then
              1. Return *false*.
            1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_a_.[[Return]], _b_.[[Return]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
          1. Return *true*.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Signatures are compared position-wise, so the order in which a name's overloads are declared is part of the function type. Canonicalization does not reorder them, because there is no order over signatures that is both total and meaningful, and because the declaration order is already observable through the reflected `signatures` list.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-issignaturesubtype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsSignatureSubtype (
            _a_: a Signature Record,
            _b_: a Signature Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether a function with the signature _a_ may be used where the signature _b_ is required.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _a_.[[Untyped]] is *true*, return *true*.
          1. If _a_ requires more arguments than _b_ may supply, return *false*.
          1. For each integer _j_ such that 0 &le; _j_ and _j_ &lt; the number of elements of _b_.[[Parameters]], do
            1. Let _q_ be _b_.[[Parameters]][_j_].
            1. If _a_.[[Parameters]] has no element at index _j_ and no element of _a_.[[Parameters]] has [[Rest]] *true*, return *false*.
            1. Let _p_ be the element of _a_.[[Parameters]] that receives the argument at index _j_.
            1. If _p_.[[Reference]] is not _q_.[[Reference]], return *false*.
            1. If IsSubtype(_q_.[[Type]], _p_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
          1. If _b_.[[Return]].[[Kind]] is ~void~, return *true*.
          1. Return IsSubtype(_a_.[[Return]], _b_.[[Return]], _assumptions_).
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Parameters are contravariant and the return is covariant, which is the standard rule and the only one that is sound: a function used where `(uint8) =&gt; uint8` is required will be handed a `uint8`, so it must accept at least every `uint8`, and its result will be used as a `uint8`, so it must produce only `uint8` values. A `ref` parameter is invariant because it is a location that is both read and written, so a mismatch in either direction is unsound; this is the parameter-level counterpart of the ~reference~ rule in <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>.</p>
          <p>A function that accepts fewer arguments than the target supplies is admitted, since ECMAScript already ignores extra arguments and rejecting it would make every callback that omits an unused parameter unusable. A `void` return is required of nothing, since a caller that has declared it will not use the result.</p>
          <p>This admission does not agree with the arity rule of <emu-xref href="#sec-resolveoverload"></emu-xref>, and the disagreement is worth stating. A call of `f` declared as `function f(a: uint8) {}` with two arguments selects no signature and is an error, because a signature is viable only for an argument list its arity accepts. But `f` is assignable to `(uint8, string) =&gt; void` by the rule above, and a call through a binding of that type reaches `f` with the second argument present and is not an error. The same call is therefore rejected when written directly and permitted through a function type. Either extra arguments are acceptable, in which case overload resolution should admit them and prefer the signature that uses the most, or they are not, in which case a function that ignores a parameter should not satisfy a type that supplies it and every such callback needs its parameter list widened. The design states the first rule and not the second, and this specification supplies the second in the shape ECMAScript's existing tolerance of extra arguments suggests. The committee should settle which of the two governs.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-isfunctionsubtype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsFunctionSubtype (
            _s_: a ~function~ Type Record,
            _t_: a ~function~ Type Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether every value of the function type _s_ is a value of the function type _t_.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. For each element _b_ of _t_.[[Signatures]], do
            1. If there is no element _a_ of _s_.[[Signatures]] such that IsSignatureSubtype(_a_, _b_, _assumptions_) is *true*, return *false*.
          1. Return *true*.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>An overloaded function type is the conjunction of its signatures, so a function satisfies it by satisfying each one, possibly with a different signature for each. This is why the quantifiers run this way round: every signature the target promises must be met by some signature the source provides, and a source may provide more.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-overload-resolution">
      <h1>Overload Resolution</h1>
      <p>An overloaded name evaluates to a single function object that resolves at the call site. Its `name` is the shared name, its `length` is the smallest parameter count among its signatures, and `call`, `apply`, and `bind` resolve by the same rules. Individual signatures are not addressable as properties; they are exposed by the function reflection of the decorators extension.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-resolveoverload" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          ResolveOverload (
            _signatures_: a List of Signature Records,
            _args_: a List of Parse Nodes,
            _contextualType_: a Type Record or ~none~,
          ): either a Signature Record, ~none~, or ~ambiguous~
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It selects the signature a call invokes.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. Let _viable_ be a new empty List.
          1. For each element _sig_ of _signatures_, do
            1. If _args_ does not satisfy the arity of _sig_.[[Parameters]], accounting for optional parameters, defaults, and a rest parameter, then
              1. Continue.
            1. If some element of _args_ is not assignable to the type of the parameter that receives it, then
              1. Continue.
            1. If _contextualType_ is not ~none~ and IsAssignable(_sig_.[[Return]], _contextualType_) is *false*, then
              1. Continue.
            1. Append _sig_ to _viable_.
          1. If _viable_ is empty, return ~none~.
          1. For each element _sig_ of _viable_, do
            1. Let _rank_ be the greatest rank in <emu-xref href="#table-argument-match-ranks"></emu-xref> required by any element of _args_ to match its parameter in _sig_.
            1. Let _sig_'s worst rank be _rank_.
          1. Let _best_ be the elements of _viable_ whose worst rank is least.
          1. If _best_ has exactly one element, return that element.
          1. Return ~ambiguous~.
        </emu-alg>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-table id="table-argument-match-ranks" caption="Argument Match Ranks">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Rank</th><th>The argument matches its parameter by</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1</td><td>Being of exactly the parameter's type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2</td><td>Being an untyped literal that takes the parameter's type, ordered among competing parameter types by <emu-xref href="#table-literal-ranking"></emu-xref>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>A user-defined conversion (<emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-conversions"></emu-xref>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4</td><td>Binding to a signature whose [[Untyped]] is *true*.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <p>It is a type error if ResolveOverload returns ~none~, and it is a type error if it returns ~ambiguous~. Where an argument has the `any` type the resolution is performed at run time on the argument's runtime type, and the same errors are thrown as a *TypeError* there.</p>

      <p>Two signatures declared for one name must not be ambiguous for any argument list. It is a type error to declare a signature that is viable for the same argument list as an existing one at the same rank.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Ranking by the worst match rather than by a sum keeps the rule from trading a bad match on one argument against a good one on another, which is where the ranking rules of C++ become hard to predict. A typed argument never ranks below 1: a typed argument of the wrong type is not viable at all, so it is never a question of how well it matches.</p>
        <p>An untyped function is a catch-all because its signature has [[Untyped]] *true*, which ranks last. Given `function f() {}` and `function f(a: uint8) {}`, the call `f(1)` selects the typed signature, since the literal ranks 2 against the catch-all's 4, while `f(1, 2)` selects the untyped one, since the typed signature's arity does not accept two arguments and it is not viable. A function that takes no arguments and is nonetheless typed is written by declaring the return type, as `function f(): void {}`, which makes [[Untyped]] *false* and so makes `f(1)` an error.</p>
        <p>The ambiguity rule reaches further than duplicate parameter lists. `function f(a: uint8) {}` and `function f(a: uint8, b: string = 'b') {}` are ambiguous, because the default makes the second viable for a single `uint8` argument at the same rank; so are `function f(a: float32): void {}` and `function f(...a: [].&lt;float32&gt;): void {}`, because the rest parameter covers the one-argument call. A default or a rest parameter expands a signature into a family of arities, and it is the family that must not collide.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-overloading-on-return-type">
      <h1>Overloading on Return Type</h1>
      <p>Because a signature is identified by its return type as well as its parameter types, two signatures may differ only in their return. The return type does not participate in ranking; it participates in viability, through the contextual type of the call (<emu-xref href="#sec-contextual-types"></emu-xref>).</p>

      <p>The contextual type of a call is the type its position requires. Where a call has no contextual type and more than one signature remains viable, the call is ~ambiguous~ and it is a type error.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Given `function f(): uint32` and `function f(): string`, the call `f()` alone is an error, `const a: string = f();` selects the second, and `g(f())` selects the first where `g` takes a `uint32`, because the parameter supplies the contextual type. `h(f())` is an error where `h` is itself overloaded on `uint8` and `string`, since an argument of a call with more than one applicable signature has no contextual type. The circularity is real and is resolved by rejecting the call rather than by guessing.</p>
        <p>Return-type overloading exists for the operators. A SIMD comparison returns either a vector of lane results or a compact mask, which Intel's intrinsics distinguish by name and which real types cannot: `operator&lt;(v: int32x4): int32x4` and `operator&lt;(v: int32x4): boolean8` are the same signature but for the return. `const a: int32x4 = x == y;` and `const b: boolean8 = x == y;` select between them, and the comparison written with no contextual type is an error rather than a default.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-completing-the-literal-ranking">
      <h1>The Literal Ranking Completed</h1>
      <p><emu-xref href="#table-literal-ranking"></emu-xref> orders the numeric types a literal may take. It is completed here for the types it omits, which are the ones a call may nonetheless select.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-literal-ranking-completion" caption="Literal Ranking of the Remaining Numeric Types">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Rank</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>`number`</td><td>Ahead of `float64`, and so ahead of every other numeric type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`int.&lt;N&gt;` and `uint.&lt;N&gt;` for an _N_ that is not a named shorthand</td><td>Among the widths of their family, in the same order: a narrower width after a wider one. `uint.&lt;24&gt;` ranks after `uint32` and before `uint16`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`rational.&lt;N&gt;`</td><td>After every integer type. A wider _N_ before a narrower one.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`complex.&lt;T&gt;` and `vector.&lt;T, N&gt;`</td><td>Not ranked. A literal does not take either type, so no signature is selected for a literal argument by them.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Ranking `number` first is the repair <emu-xref href="#sec-literal-overload-ranking"></emu-xref> records. The design's ranking begins at `float64` and justifies it on the ground that Number is a `float64` and the conversion is exact, which is the argument for ranking `number` itself first: it is the type a literal takes with no contextual type, and the type an untyped program computes with. Without it, `f(a: number)` against `f(a: float32)` has no answer for `f(1)`. This changes which function a call selects and so is a decision for the committee rather than an editorial repair, but leaving it out leaves a common case undefined.</p>
        <p>Placing the rationals after the integers keeps a literal that is an integer selecting an integer signature, which is what a program that declares both would expect. Within a family a wider width ranks first, following the design's own order, which prefers the type that can represent the most.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-typed-arrow-functions">
      <h1>Arrow Functions</h1>
      <p>An arrow function's parameters may carry annotations and its body may carry a return annotation. The annotations occupy the positions <emu-xref href="#sec-type-annotations"></emu-xref> gives them, within the cover grammar the arrow syntax already uses.</p>

      <emu-grammar type="definition">
        ArrowFunction[In, Yield, Await] :
          ArrowParameters[?Yield, ?Await] <ins>TypeAnnotation[?Yield, ?Await]?</ins> [no LineTerminator here] `=>` ConciseBody[?In]
      </emu-grammar>

      <p>When the production <emu-grammar>ArrowParameters : CoverParenthesizedExpressionAndArrowParameterList</emu-grammar> is refined using |ArrowFormalParameters|, a parameter may carry the annotations of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-annotations"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`(x: uint8): uint8 =&gt; x * x` is therefore an arrow function of one `uint8` parameter returning a `uint8`. The return annotation sits between the parameters and the `=&gt;`, which is the only position available, and it is what distinguishes an annotated arrow from a function type: `(uint8) =&gt; uint8` in a type position is a type, while `(x: uint8): uint8 =&gt; x * x` in an expression position is a function. An arrow function is not overloadable, since it has no name to overload.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-classes-interfaces-and-enums">
    <h1>Classes, Interfaces, and Enums</h1>
    <p>This clause defines the nominal and structural types a program declares: the object type and its identity and subtyping, which complete the last cases <emu-xref href="#sec-type-system-foundations"></emu-xref> defers; the rules that make a class a value type; interfaces; enums; and the sealed hierarchy that gives a closed union.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-object-types-semantics">
      <h1>Object Types</h1>
      <p>A <dfn id="property-type-record">Property Type Record</dfn> describes one member of an ~object~ type. It has a [[Key]] (a property key), a [[Type]] (a Type Record), an [[Optional]] field (a Boolean), a [[Readonly]] field (a Boolean), and an [[Initial]] field (an ECMAScript language value or ~none~, the member's declared default).</p>

      <p>An <dfn id="index-signature-record">Index Signature Record</dfn> has a [[KeyType]] and a [[ValueType]], each a Type Record. No production of the type grammar writes one: an object type acquires index signatures through construction (<emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-maketype"></emu-xref>), they take part in identity below and in `keyof` (<emu-xref href="#sec-keyof"></emu-xref>), and their membership and subtype rules are parked with the objects work that will write the source syntax.</p>

      <emu-clause id="sec-sameobjecttype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          SameObjectType (
            _s_: an ~object~ Type Record,
            _t_: an ~object~ Type Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether _s_ and _t_ are the same object type.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. If _s_.[[Properties]] and _t_.[[Properties]] do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
          1. For each element _p_ of _s_.[[Properties]], do
            1. Let _q_ be the element of _t_.[[Properties]] whose [[Key]] is _p_.[[Key]], or ~empty~ if there is none.
            1. If _q_ is ~empty~, return *false*.
            1. If _p_.[[Optional]] is not _q_.[[Optional]], return *false*.
            1. If _p_.[[Readonly]] is not _q_.[[Readonly]], return *false*.
            1. If _p_.[[Initial]] is ~none~ or _q_.[[Initial]] is ~none~, then
              1. If _p_.[[Initial]] is not ~none~ or _q_.[[Initial]] is not ~none~, return *false*.
            1. Else if SameValue(_p_.[[Initial]], _q_.[[Initial]]) is *false*, then
              1. Return *false*.
            1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_p_.[[Type]], _q_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
          1. If _s_.[[IndexSignatures]] and _t_.[[IndexSignatures]] do not have the same number of elements, return *false*.
          1. For each integer _j_ such that 0 &le; _j_ and _j_ &lt; the number of elements of _s_.[[IndexSignatures]], do
            1. Let _a_ be _s_.[[IndexSignatures]][_j_].
            1. Let _b_ be _t_.[[IndexSignatures]][_j_].
            1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_a_.[[KeyType]], _b_.[[KeyType]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_a_.[[ValueType]], _b_.[[ValueType]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
          1. Return *true*.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>Members are matched by key rather than by position, so the order in which an object type lists them is not part of its identity and `{ x: float32, y: float32 }` and `{ y: float32, x: float32 }` are one type. Canonicalization orders the [[Properties]] of an ~object~ Type Record by key, which is what allows the interning of <emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref> to give them one Type Object, and orders the [[IndexSignatures]] by the fixed total order on their [[KeyType]]s. That ordering serves identity; whether the source's own member order should additionally be preserved for display and reflection, carried outside the canonical form the way a parameter's name already is (<emu-xref href="#sec-signature-records"></emu-xref>), is open. Nothing today records it, so a reflected object type lists its properties in key order whatever order the source wrote.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <emu-clause id="sec-isobjectsubtype" type="abstract operation">
        <h1>
          IsObjectSubtype (
            _s_: an ~object~ Type Record,
            _t_: an ~object~ Type Record,
            _assumptions_: a List of Records that have [[First]] and [[Second]] fields,
          ): a Boolean
        </h1>
        <dl class="header">
          <dt>description</dt>
          <dd>It determines whether every value of the object type _s_ is a value of the object type _t_.</dd>
        </dl>
        <emu-alg>
          1. For each element _q_ of _t_.[[Properties]], do
            1. Let _p_ be the element of _s_.[[Properties]] whose [[Key]] is _q_.[[Key]], or ~empty~ if there is none.
            1. If _p_ is ~empty~, then
              1. If _q_.[[Optional]] is *false*, return *false*.
              1. Continue.
            1. If _p_.[[Optional]] is *true* and _q_.[[Optional]] is *false*, return *false*.
            1. If _q_.[[Readonly]] is *false* and _p_.[[Readonly]] is *true*, return *false*.
            1. If _q_.[[Readonly]] is *true*, then
              1. If IsSubtype(_p_.[[Type]], _q_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
            1. Else,
              1. If SameTypeWithAssumptions(_p_.[[Type]], _q_.[[Type]], _assumptions_) is *false*, return *false*.
          1. Return *true*.
        </emu-alg>
        <emu-note>
          <p>An object type is subtyped in width, so a type with more members is a subtype of one with fewer: an object that has everything `{ x: float32 }` requires is usable where that type is required, whatever else it has.</p>
          <p>It is subtyped in depth only through a `readonly` member. A `readonly` member is covariant, since a value read from it and never written through it need only be of the required type. A writable member is invariant, because covariance there is unsound: were `{ x: Meter }` a subtype of `{ x: float32 }`, a bare `float32` could be written through the supertype view into a slot the program believes holds a `Meter`. This is the same rule the ~reference~ and ~array~ kinds already follow in <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>, and it is the point at which this proposal parts company with an erasable type system, which can afford covariance there because nothing depends on the claim. Here the layout does.</p>
        </emu-note>
      </emu-clause>

      <p>A boundary that accepts a value into a position of an ~object~ type does not impose that type's members on the value. The value's own properties keep the types they were declared with, and a property the value declared without a type keeps the `any` type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>This answers the question <emu-xref href="#sec-isoftype"></emu-xref> raises and it answers it in the direction that admits the unsoundness, because the alternative is worse. Imposing the target's member types would mean that passing a plain object to a `{ x: uint8 }` position silently retypes the object for every other holder of it, which is an action at a distance no other boundary performs, and would make the same object have different property types depending on where it had been. The consequence is that a check on a structural type is a statement about the value at the moment it crossed, not a guarantee about it afterwards, and a later write through an untyped alias can invalidate it. A program that wants the guarantee declares the property's type with the `{ (x: uint8): 1 }` form of the object typing section, or uses a class, where the field's type is a property of the layout.</p>
        <p>A narrowing of a property, as in `if (o.f instanceof T)`, follows from the same fact and is admitted only where the property cannot change between the test and the use: a `readonly` field of a sealed typed class, whose write is a type error after construction. Elsewhere the narrowing does not hold, since `o.f` may be a getter or may be assigned in between, and <emu-xref href="#sec-narrowing"></emu-xref> therefore narrows bindings rather than paths.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-typed-classes">
      <h1>Typed Classes</h1>
      <p>A class is <dfn id="typed-class">typed</dfn> when at least one of its public or private fields carries a type annotation. A typed class is automatically sealed and its prototype frozen, as <emu-xref href="#sec-typed-storage"></emu-xref> specifies. A class declared `dynamic` is not sealed and is not a value type.</p>

      <p>A typed class is a <dfn id="value-type-class">value type class</dfn> when every one of its fields has a type that is a value type. Instances of a value type class are values in the sense of <emu-xref href="#sec-value-types"></emu-xref>: they are laid out contiguously, they are stored inline in a field or an array element of that type, and assigning one copies it. It is a type error for a value type class to contain itself, directly or through a cycle of value type fields, since the layout would have no finite size. A field that closes such a cycle is written `T | null`, which is a reference.</p>

      <p>A field with no initializer holds the default value of its type (<emu-xref href="#sec-defaultvalueof"></emu-xref>), and it is a type error to declare a field whose type has no default and give it no initializer.</p>

      <p>`===` on two instances of a value type class compares them field by field, since the identity of a value type is its value. `===` on two instances of a class that is not a value type compares references.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>That a value type class defaults field by field means an instance can come into existence without its constructor running, which <emu-xref href="#sec-default-values"></emu-xref> flags. This clause endorses it, because the design already requires it in two places and the alternative would break both. `let d: [10].&lt;A&gt;;` must hold ten zero-filled instances for the memory layout extension's contiguous array to exist at all, and a conversion from a matching object literal, `{ ... } := Vector3`, is specified to fill the layout directly and run no constructor. A value type class is therefore a shape with a zero, not an object with an invariant its constructor establishes, and a class that needs its constructor to run states that by holding a field whose type has no default, which makes the zero-filled form a type error. This is a real constraint on what a value type class can promise, and it should be stated in the design rather than left to follow from the array case.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-interfaces-semantics">
      <h1>Interfaces</h1>
      <p>An interface declares a contract. Its type is a ~nominal~ type whose [[Declaration]] is the interface declaration, and a class that implements it is a subtype of it by <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>, which follows the declared hierarchy. An interface may also type an object, an array, or a function structurally.</p>

      <p>A class that implements an interface cannot remove the contract: deleting a member the interface requires throws a *TypeError* exception, and this holds through a subclass, a reference, and reflection.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>An interface is nominal where a class declares that it implements one and structural where a value is checked against it, which are two questions rather than one contradiction: the first asks whether a declaration promised the contract, the second whether a value meets it. `IsOfType` decides the second by <emu-xref href="#sec-isoftype"></emu-xref>, so an object that has the members satisfies an interface-typed position whether or not any class declared it.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-enums">
      <h1>Enums</h1>
      <p>An enum declaration introduces a ~nominal~ type whose values are its enumerators. The type after `:` is the enum's <dfn id="underlying-type">underlying type</dfn>, and an enum declared without one has the underlying type `int32`. Any type may be an underlying type, including a function type and `symbol`.</p>

      <p>An enumerator with no initializer takes the value after the one before it, and the first takes 0. An enumerator initialized with a function of two parameters is given the result of calling that function with the enumerator's index and its name as a String, and a following enumerator with no initializer is given the result of calling the same function with its own index and name. Such a function is not a closure.</p>

      <p>An enum type is a subtype of its underlying type, so a value of an enum type is usable wherever the underlying type is required and no conversion is written. The reverse is explicit: calling the enum type with a value of the underlying type returns the enumerator whose value it is, and throws a *TypeError* when it is not one of them.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The one-way rule is the rule of C#, Rust, and Swift. It is what lets a bitmask index such as `comp / 32` read directly while `Component(id)` remains a deliberate and validated step, and it is why an enum can be used for arithmetic, indexing, and comparison without a cast.</p>
        <p>An enum's subtyping is a further case of the ~primitive~ and ~nominal~ rules in <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>, which follow a declared class hierarchy and a metadata parameterization but do not reach an enum's underlying type. It is stated here rather than there because it is the same shape of relation, a type that refines another and is subsumed into it, and the specification should ultimately give the three one rule rather than three.</p>
        <p>`Reflect.typeOf(Count.Zero)` reports `Count`, by the rule of <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-typeof"></emu-xref> that a value's runtime type is the most specific type of which it is a value. This does not make the enumerator anything other than a value the underlying type also accepts: membership in `int32` follows from `Count` being a subtype of it, not from a second runtime type, so the uniqueness <emu-xref href="#sec-runtimetypeof"></emu-xref> requires is preserved and no conversion is performed. The case is exactly parallel to a metadata parameterization, where `Reflect.typeOf` of a `Meter` is `float32.&lt;{ m: 1 }&gt;` and not `float32`, while `m instanceof float32` is nonetheless *true*.</p>
        <p>What remains is that this specification now has three relations of one shape: a metadata parameterization refining its primitive, an enum refining its underlying type, and a class extending its base. Each is a separate step of <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>. They would be better given one rule, and the design would be better stating the enum case as subtyping rather than as an implicit conversion, which is what it is: describing it as a conversion is what makes it look like a fifth exception to <emu-xref href="#table-implicit-conversions"></emu-xref> when it is not an exception at all.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-sealed-classes">
      <h1>Sealed Classes</h1>
      <p>A class declared `sealed` may not be extended outside the module that declares it, so its subclasses are a fixed and known set. A sealed class is a reference type rather than a value type, so a field of a sealed type holds an instance of any of its subclasses directly rather than through a nullable union.</p>

      <p>A `sealed abstract` class can be neither instantiated nor extended outside its module. Its concrete subclasses are therefore a closed set with no case among them for the base, and a `switch` over a value of its type is exhaustive when it has a case for each subclass.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>This is the algebraic data type, assembled from parts the proposal has for other reasons rather than from a new construct. The cases are the subclasses, the case labels are their type objects, which are values because types are values, and the match is the `switch` the control structures section already defines. What makes it work is that the set is closed: exhaustiveness is a claim about a hierarchy no other module can extend, which is why it is reserved to a sealed class and an enum and is deliberately not available for a union of literal types, whose members are not a declaration anyone owns.</p>
        <p>That a sealed class is a reference type is what lets a field hold a subclass instance polymorphically. A value type class cannot, since its field embeds the base slice of the layout and has no room for a subclass, which is why the two forms differ and why holding a value type class polymorphically is spelled `T | null`.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-reflection">
    <h1>Reflection</h1>
    <p>This clause defines what a program observes of a type at run time: the operation that reports a value's type, the opacity of a Type Object, the operation that exposes a type's structure, and the effect of a declared type on the existing reflective operations.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-reflect-typeof">
      <h1>Reflect.typeOf ( _value_ )</h1>
      <p>This function performs the following steps when called:</p>
      <emu-alg>
        1. Return GetTypeObject(RuntimeTypeOf(_value_)).
      </emu-alg>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`Reflect.typeOf` reports the most specific type of which the value is a value, not every type it belongs to. For a `uint8` binding it returns `uint8`; for a value of the metadata-parameterized `Meter` it returns `float32.&lt;{ m: 1 }&gt;`, the full parameterization, which is how reflection obtains constraint information at run time. Membership in a less specific type is not a second runtime type but a consequence of subtyping, which is why `m instanceof float32` is *true* while `Reflect.typeOf(m)` is not `float32`.</p>
        <p>It is the companion of `typeof`, which is unchanged and reports the underlying language type: `typeof a` is *"number"* for a `uint8` binding while `Reflect.typeOf(a)` is `uint8`. `typeof` on a Type Object is *"object"*, since a Type Object is an Object, and `typeof uint8 === "object"` therefore doubles as feature detection for this proposal.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-type-object-opacity">
      <h1>The Opacity of a Type Object</h1>
      <p>A Type Object exposes no property that reveals the structure of the type it denotes. Given the Type Object for `Player | null` no property yields its members, and given the one for `[].&lt;uint32&gt;` no property yields its element type or its extent. A Type Object's [[TypeRecord]] is an internal slot and is reachable only through <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-getreflection"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <p>One exception is display: a Type Object has a `toString` method returning the canonical source form of the type it denotes, so calling `String` on the Type Object for `'a' | 'b'` yields the String *"'a' | 'b'"*. The printed form exists for diagnostics and authored error messages, not for inspection: its format follows the canonical form and is therefore stable, but parsing it is not the supported way to read a type's structure, which remains <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-getreflection"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Opacity is what lets the interning of <emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref> be an implementation strategy rather than an obligation to materialize a graph. An engine that represents `[].&lt;uint32&gt;` as a tag rather than as an object with an `element` property is conforming, and a program cannot tell. It also keeps the type-object surface from becoming a second, weaker reflection API alongside the real one: there is one way to inspect a type, and it is named.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-reflect-getreflection">
      <h1>Structural Reflection</h1>
      <p>`Reflect.getReflection.&lt;Reflect.Type&gt;(_t_)` returns a reflection node describing the structure of the type _t_ denotes. The node has a `kind` property whose value is a String naming the [[Kind]] of _t_'s Type Record, and the further properties of <emu-xref href="#table-reflection-nodes"></emu-xref>. Every property of a node that denotes a type holds a Type Object, so a walker recurses by reflecting it in turn.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-reflection-nodes" caption="Reflection Nodes by Kind">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>`kind`</th><th>Further properties</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>*"primitive"*</td><td>`type`, the Type Object itself; `generic`, either *undefined* or a record with `base` (a Type Object) and `arguments` (a List of Type Objects and values), the decomposition of a generic instantiation. This one node covers every named leaf: the built-in primitives, classes, interfaces, enums, and the `any`, `void`, and `type` types.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"literal"*</td><td>`value`, a String, Number, Boolean, or BigInt; `base`, a Type Object.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"parameterized"*</td><td>`base`, a Type Object; `metadata`, an object: the metadata half of a parameterization such as `float32.&lt;{ m: 1 }&gt;`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"union"*</td><td>`arms`, a List of Type Objects, in the canonical order; empty for the `never` type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"intersection"*</td><td>`members`, a List of Type Objects, in the canonical order.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"tuple"*</td><td>`elements`, a List of records with `type` (a Type Object), `rest`, and `initial`.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"array"*</td><td>`element`, a Type Object; `extent`, a non-negative integer or *undefined* for a dynamic length.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"object"*</td><td>`properties`, a List of records with `name` (a String or Symbol), `type` (a Type Object), `optional`, `readonly`, and `initial`; `indexSignatures`, a List of records with `key` and `value` (Type Objects).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"function"*</td><td>`signatures`, in declaration order, each a record with `parameters` (records with `type`, `name`, `index`, `optional`, `rest`, `initial`, and `metadata`), `return` (a record with `type` and `metadata`), and `thisType` (a Type Object or *undefined*). The `metadata` properties are supplied by the decorators extension.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"reference"*</td><td>`target`, a Type Object: the `ref` borrow type of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-expressions"></emu-xref>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>*"cycle"*</td><td>`name`, a String: the reader-facing back-edge at which a recursive type closes. It appears in reflection output only and is not accepted by construction.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The node kinds and the Type Record kinds of <emu-xref href="#table-type-record-kinds"></emu-xref> correspond, and the correspondence now round-trips: every kind is readable, and writable through <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-maketype"></emu-xref>, with three deliberate wrinkles. The named leaves, ~primitive~ and ~nominal~ alike and with them `any`, `void`, and `type`, share the one *"primitive"* node, whose payload is the interned Type Object itself with a generic instantiation additionally decomposed, so a leaf is opaque to a walker exactly as <emu-xref href="#sec-type-object-opacity"></emu-xref> requires and a nominal type never exposes its declaration. A metadata parameterization reads and rebuilds through *"parameterized"*, whose metadata is the corresponding member of the ~primitive~ Record's [[Arguments]]. And the ~application~ kind has no node at all, because specialization evaluates every deferred application before any code runs, so reflection cannot encounter one.</p>
        <p>The same `Reflect.getReflection` reflects a declaration's members, keyed on the declaration rather than on a type, which is how a class's fields, a function's parameters, and an enum's enumerators are exposed. That context and the rest of the reflection facility, including its metadata and a `Reflect.ClassConstructor` context for construct signatures, are defined by the decorators extension. This clause defines only the type-object context it operates on.</p>
        <p>A union's arms are reflected in the canonical order rather than in the order written, since canonicalization has already reordered them and the Type Object is shared with every other spelling of the same type. A function's signatures are reflected in declaration order, which <emu-xref href="#sec-samefunctiontype"></emu-xref> preserves for this reason.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-reflect-maketype">
      <h1>Reflect.makeType ( _node_ )</h1>
      <p>The input is structural: any object matching a node's shape in <emu-xref href="#table-reflection-nodes"></emu-xref> describes that node, and a Type Object anywhere within it contributes its [[TypeRecord]]. This function performs the following steps when called:</p>
      <emu-alg>
        1. If _node_ is not an Object matching a node's shape in <emu-xref href="#table-reflection-nodes"></emu-xref>, throw a *TypeError* exception.
        1. Let _record_ be the Type Record that _node_, read as a description, describes.
        1. If _record_ describes a type that no declaration could introduce, throw a *TypeError* exception with the message the equivalent source declaration produces.
        1. Return GetTypeObject(_record_).
      </emu-alg>
      <p>For every type _T_, `Reflect.makeType(Reflect.getReflection.&lt;Reflect.Type&gt;(`_T_`))` is _T_. Construction canonicalizes and interns by <emu-xref href="#sec-canonicalizetype"></emu-xref> and <emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref>, the same operations that give a source-written type its identity, which is what makes the round trip the identity function rather than an equivalence.</p>
      <emu-note>
        <p>Canonicalization is where invalidity is caught: a node describing an infinite value-type layout, an intersection of distinct value types, or an index signature with an illegal key type fails exactly as the equivalent declaration fails, with the same message, so a builder's misuse reads as the misuse it is. A *"cycle"* node is not accepted, since it is reflection output; a constructed cycle arises only from the fixpoint of <emu-xref href="#sec-evaluatebuildercall"></emu-xref>. The function is compile-time evaluable, and at run time it is an ordinary function returning the same interned objects, so `String(Reflect.makeType(&hellip;))` prints the canonical form of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-object-opacity"></emu-xref>.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-reflect-isassignable">
      <h1>Reflect.isAssignable ( _source_, _target_ )</h1>
      <p>This function performs the following steps when called:</p>
      <emu-alg>
        1. If _source_ is not a Type Object or _target_ is not a Type Object, throw a *TypeError* exception.
        1. Return IsAssignable(_source_.[[TypeRecord]], _target_.[[TypeRecord]]).
      </emu-alg>
      <emu-note>
        <p>This is the checker's own judgment (<emu-xref href="#sec-isassignable"></emu-xref>) exposed unchanged, so what a builder branches on and what the checker enforces cannot disagree; the conditional types of an erased system are written `Reflect.isAssignable(T, U) ? X : Y` inside a builder. It is deliberately the assignability relation rather than a new one: mutual assignability is composed from it, and identity is `===` by interning. The function is compile-time evaluable.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-reflect-never">
      <h1>Reflect.never</h1>
      <p>The initial value of `Reflect.never` is the Type Object of the `never` type (<emu-xref href="#sec-never-type"></emu-xref>). This property has the attributes { [[Writable]]: *false*, [[Enumerable]]: *false*, [[Configurable]]: *false* }.</p>
      <emu-note>
        <p>A name for the empty union, so that code need not spell it as a construction; `Reflect.makeType({ kind: 'union', arms: [] })` returns the same object.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-reflection-and-declared-types">
      <h1>Reflection and Declared Types</h1>
      <p>The existing reflective operations respect a declared type. `Reflect.set` on a property with a declared type _t_ performs RequireType(_value_, _t_) and throws where the value does not satisfy it. `Reflect.get` returns the property's value, which is of its declared type. `Reflect.defineProperty` accepts a `type` key in the property descriptor, whose value is a Type Object, and a descriptor with a `type` and no `value` gives the property the default value of that type (<emu-xref href="#sec-defaultvalueof"></emu-xref>). `Reflect.deleteProperty` on a property with a declared type, and on a member required by an implemented interface, throws a *TypeError* exception.</p>

      <p>A Proxy constructed with a type argument _T_ has a [[RuntimeType]] internal slot whose value is _T_'s Type Record, so `Reflect.typeOf` reports _T_ rather than the shape of its target, and its traps are checked against _T_. A Proxy constructed without one has no such slot and is of the `any` type. Each trap result for a property with a declared type, whether the type is declared by _T_ or carried by the target as a typed own property, is checked against that type at the trap boundary. Constructing a Proxy whose target is an instance of a typed class or a typed array throws a *TypeError* exception: such a value is backed by a layout rather than a property table, a field access does not consult a handler, and there is no point at which a trap could correctly run.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Reflection is a boundary in the sense of <emu-xref href="#table-check-sites"></emu-xref>, not an exception to it. A value entering a typed position through `Reflect.set` is checked exactly as one entering through an assignment, which is what keeps a typed field's type a fact about its storage: were reflection able to write past the check, an engine could not lay the field out on the strength of its type, and the proposal's premise would not hold. That a typed property cannot be deleted is the same guarantee in the other direction, since a layout with a hole in it is not the layout the type described.</p>
        <p>A Proxy reporting the type it was constructed with rather than its target's shape is what makes the trap checks meaningful: the contract a proxy enforces is the one it was given, and reporting anything else would describe a value the program never promised.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-numeric-library">
    <h1>The Numeric Library</h1>
    <p>This clause defines the library the numeric types need: the overloading of the existing functions so that they preserve the type they are given, the named arithmetic forms that check or saturate rather than wrap, the floored division pair, and the parsing of a string into a numeric type.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-overloading-of-the-standard-library">
      <h1>Overloading of the Existing Functions</h1>
      <p>The functions of the Math object, and the other library functions that take or return a numeric value, are overloaded for the numeric types by <emu-xref href="#sec-overload-resolution"></emu-xref>. A signature taking a value of a numeric type _T_ returns a value of _T_ where its result is a number of the same kind, so no conversion is written at a call.</p>

      <p>The `length` of an array is a `uint32`.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>This is what makes the conversion rule livable rather than merely strict. `Math.clz32` of a `uint32` is a `uint32`, `Math.min` of two `float32` values is a `float32`, and a `uint32` loop counter compares against `array.length` without a cast, because the library meets the program where it is. A library that returned a Number from every function would force a conversion at every call and would make typed code read worse than untyped code, which is the failure mode the design is avoiding.</p>
        <p>The existing signatures are unchanged, so `Math.min` of two Numbers is a Number and every existing program means what it meant. The overloads are additions, and a call with untyped literal arguments selects among them by <emu-xref href="#table-literal-ranking"></emu-xref>, which ranks `number` first and so keeps an untyped call on the signature it selects today.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-checked-and-saturating-arithmetic">
      <h1>Checked and Saturating Arithmetic</h1>
      <p>The operators wrap on overflow (<emu-xref href="#sec-integer-operations"></emu-xref>). Where wrapping is not wanted, the named forms of <emu-xref href="#table-checked-and-saturating"></emu-xref> are used. Each is overloaded for every integer type and returns a value of its operands' type.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-checked-and-saturating" caption="Checked and Saturating Forms">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Form</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>`Math.addChecked`, `Math.subChecked`, `Math.mulChecked`, `Math.divChecked`</td><td>The exact result where the type can represent it. Otherwise a *RangeError*.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>`Math.addSaturating`, `Math.subSaturating`, `Math.mulSaturating`, `Math.divSaturating`</td><td>The exact result where the type can represent it. Otherwise the nearest value of the type, which is its greatest value when the exact result exceeds it and its least when the exact result falls below it.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>Silent wrapping is the wrong answer when the value is a count rather than a bit pattern, and the right answer when it is a bit pattern rather than a count. Neither is right always, so the operator takes the case that has to be cheap and the named forms take the rest: `a + 1` on a `uint8` holding 255 is 0, `Math.addChecked(a, 1)` throws a *RangeError* exception, and `Math.addSaturating(a, 1)` is 255.</p>
        <p>These forms exist for the integer types because only there is wrapping the default. A float already saturates, to an infinity, and a decimal already raises a *RangeError*, since a decimal's range is a property of the type rather than of the format (<emu-xref href="#table-numeric-conversions"></emu-xref>). A rational already raises a *RangeError* on an unrepresentable result. Each family's overflow behaviour is therefore the one its values make available, and the named forms give the integer types the two the others have built in.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-floored-division">
      <h1>Floored Division</h1>
      <p>`Math.divFloor(_a_, _b_)` returns the exact quotient of _a_ and _b_ rounded toward negative infinity. `Math.mod(_a_, _b_)` returns the remainder whose sign follows the divisor. Both are overloaded for every integer type, and both throw a *RangeError* when _b_ is zero.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>These are the other half of the pair <emu-xref href="#sec-integer-operations"></emu-xref> describes: `Math.divFloor(_a_, _b_) * _b_ + Math.mod(_a_, _b_) = _a_` holds for the same reason the operators' identity holds, because the quotient and the remainder round the same way. They are named rather than assumed so that a program picks the pair it wants instead of receiving one by default.</p>
        <p>`Math.mod` is the `%` of Python, the `mod` of Kotlin, and the `mod` of Haskell. For a positive divisor, which is every case in which an index is being wrapped, its result equals the Euclidean remainder and is never negative, so `array[Math.mod(i, array.length)]` is always in range. Where the divisor may be negative and a non-negative result is still wanted, `Math.mod(_a_, Math.abs(_b_))` gives it, which is why no separate Euclidean pair is provided.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-parsing">
      <h1>Parsing</h1>
      <p>Each numeric type has a `parse` function. For an integer type and for `bigint` its signature is `parse(_string_, _radix_ = 10)`; for the binary floating-point, decimal, rational, and complex types it is `parse(_string_)`. It returns a value of the type the function belongs to.</p>

      <p>The accepted input is the grammar of a literal of that type, with optional leading and trailing white space and an optional sign. Numeric separators are accepted, and the form taking a radix accepts the prefix matching that radix. The entire string must be a literal of the type: no trailing text is consumed.</p>

      <p>`parse` throws a *SyntaxError* when the string is not a literal of the type, and a *RangeError* when it is a literal whose value the type cannot represent.</p>

      <p>Each type also has a `tryParse` function with the same parameters, returning a value of the type where `parse` would return one and *null* where `parse` would throw. Its return type is the union of the type and the null type.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>`parseInt` and `parseFloat` are unchanged and continue to consume a prefix and to return `NaN`. The new functions do neither, because neither is available to them: an integer type cannot represent `NaN` at all, so a failed parse has nothing to return and must throw. Doing the same for the float types is a choice rather than a necessity, and it is the right one, since a failed parse that becomes a `NaN` surfaces far from its cause. Refusing trailing text follows: a function that cannot signal failure with a value has no reason to be lenient about what it accepts.</p>
        <p>Distinguishing the two errors is what makes the failure legible. `uint8.parse('12abc')` throws a *SyntaxError* exception, since the string is not a `uint8` literal, while `uint8.parse('256')` throws a *RangeError* exception, since it is a literal and the value is out of range. This is the same distinction <emu-xref href="#table-out-of-range-treatment"></emu-xref> draws between a value of the wrong type and a value of the right type out of range.</p>
        <p>`tryParse` returning a nullable union rather than a sentinel is what lets the failure be handled by narrowing (<emu-xref href="#sec-narrowing"></emu-xref>): the result is a `uint8` in the branch that tests it against *null* and needs no cast there. A `string` is deliberately not a conversion source for a numeric type, so `let c: uint8 = '1';` is a type error and the parse is always written.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-arrays">
    <h1>Arrays and Tuples</h1>
    <p>This clause completes the ~array~ and ~tuple~ kinds: the membership test <emu-xref href="#sec-isoftype"></emu-xref> defers, the default value of a tuple, and the checking of an element store.</p>

    <p>A <dfn id="tuple-element-record">Tuple Element Record</dfn> describes one position of a ~tuple~ type. It has a [[Type]] (a Type Record), a [[Rest]] field (a Boolean, *true* for a `...` element), and an [[Initial]] field (an ECMAScript language value or ~none~, the position's declared default).</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-array-membership">
      <h1>Membership</h1>
      <p>For an ~array~ Type Record _t_, a value _v_ is of the type _t_ when _v_ is an Object, _v_'s length is _t_.[[Extent]] where that is not ~dynamic~, and every element of _v_ is of the type _t_.[[Element]].</p>

      <p>For a ~tuple~ Type Record _t_, a value _v_ is of the type _t_ when _v_ is an Object, _v_'s length is at least the number of elements of _t_.[[Elements]] whose [[Rest]] is *false* and [[Initial]] is ~none~ and that no [[Rest]] element precedes, at most the element count where no element's [[Rest]] is *true* and unbounded otherwise, and every element of _v_ is of the [[Type]] of the element of _t_.[[Elements]] that receives it, a [[Rest]] element receiving every remainder.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>A tuple's length is a range rather than a number because a trailing position may carry a default and a position may spread an array type. `[uint8, uint32 = 10]` accepts a one-element and a two-element array, which is what lets a shorter array satisfy a longer tuple return, and `[uint32, ...[].&lt;float32&gt;]` accepts any length from one upward.</p>
        <p>Checking every element is linear in the array's length, which is the cost the `any` boundary has for an array and does not have for a `uint8`. It falls only where an array of unknown type reaches a typed position; an array whose static type is already the target is not checked at all (<emu-xref href="#sec-check-elision"></emu-xref>), and a `[].&lt;uint8&gt;` passed to a `[].&lt;uint8&gt;` parameter costs nothing. Whether an implementation may instead check an element on each read, deferring the cost and spreading it, is the same question the ~object~ and ~function~ kinds raise, and it has the same answer here as there: the check as specified is eager, and a lazier one would need the wrapper the higher-order case would need.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-array-defaults-and-stores">
      <h1>Defaults and Stores</h1>
      <p>The default value of a ~tuple~ type is the array whose elements are, for each element of [[Elements]] whose [[Rest]] is *false*, its [[Initial]] where that is not ~none~ and the default value of its [[Type]] otherwise; a [[Rest]] element contributes no elements. It is ~none~ where an element has an [[Initial]] of ~none~ and a [[Type]] with no default.</p>

      <p>A store to an element of an array of element type _t_ checks the value against _t_ by <emu-xref href="#table-check-sites"></emu-xref>. `length` is a `uint32`. Deleting an element of a typed array throws a *TypeError* exception.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>This reconciles the two rules <emu-xref href="#sec-default-values"></emu-xref> leaves in tension. A tuple defaults element-wise, but an element that carries a default already has a value for its position, so the initializer is used where there is one and the type's default only where there is not. `[uint8, uint32 = 10]` therefore defaults to `[0, 10]` rather than being rejected because the second position was already spoken for.</p>
        <p>The literal element store remains the open case <emu-xref href="#sec-literal-propagation"></emu-xref> records: the design specifies `array[0] = 300` on a `[].&lt;uint8&gt;` as wrapping to 44 on the grounds of matching `Uint8Array`, while the literal rule would reject it, and the compatibility argument does not reach new syntax. Nothing in this clause resolves it, and it needs a decision.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>

  <emu-clause id="sec-extensions">
    <h1>Extensions</h1>
    <p>The design is organized as a core and a set of extensions, each of which adds types, operations, or syntax to the core rather than revising it. This clause states what an extension may do and records the hooks the preceding clauses have already named.</p>

    <emu-clause id="sec-extension-mechanism">
      <h1>The Extension Mechanism</h1>
      <p>An extension may add types to <emu-xref href="#sec-type-universe"></emu-xref>, provided each is described by a Type Record of one of the kinds of <emu-xref href="#table-type-record-kinds"></emu-xref>. It may define the operations of <emu-xref href="#sec-numeric-types-of-this-proposal"></emu-xref> for a type it adds, and may declare operators for a type that does not define them (<emu-xref href="#sec-user-defined-operators"></emu-xref>). It may add syntax, subject to the constraint the whole proposal is under: the syntax must be an error in the current language. It may add library functions, overloaded by <emu-xref href="#sec-overload-resolution"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <p>An extension may not revise the type-checking framework of <emu-xref href="#sec-type-system-foundations"></emu-xref>. In particular it may not add a kind to <emu-xref href="#table-type-record-kinds"></emu-xref>, may not change SameType or IsSubtype for a kind it did not introduce, and may not introduce an implicit conversion beyond those of <emu-xref href="#table-implicit-conversions"></emu-xref>.</p>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The last of these is the constraint worth stating explicitly, because it is the one an extension is most likely to want to break. A units extension wants `Meter` to become `float32`, a decimal extension wants a Number to become a `decimal128`, and a SIMD extension wants a scalar to broadcast into a vector. Each of these is available without an implicit conversion: the first is a metadata parameterization, which is a subtype of its base and so is subsumed rather than converted; the second is written; and the third is an operator the extension declares. The framework holds because every extension so far has been expressible within it, which is evidence that the four implicit cases are the right four rather than merely the ones that were listed first.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>

    <emu-clause id="sec-extension-hooks">
      <h1>The Hooks</h1>
      <p><emu-xref href="#table-extension-hooks"></emu-xref> lists the extensions the preceding clauses name and what each is relied on for. It is a map of the obligations this specification has incurred outward, not a specification of the extensions themselves.</p>

      <emu-table id="table-extension-hooks" caption="Extensions and the Hooks They Fill">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Extension</th><th>Relied on for</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>primitive metadata</td><td>The metadata parameterization of a primitive, which <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref> makes a subtype of its base; the meta protocol that converts between two parameterizations of one primitive at a boundary; the `DecimalContext` that fixes a decimal's scale and rounding; and the declaration of operators on a parameterized primitive.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>memory layout</td><td>`byteLength`, alignment, and the layout of a value type class, which <emu-xref href="#sec-typed-classes"></emu-xref> and <emu-xref href="#sec-default-values"></emu-xref> depend on; and the bit-field widths that make an `int.&lt;N&gt;` for a small _N_ meaningful.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SIMD</td><td>The comparison operators of the vector types, overloaded on their return type (<emu-xref href="#sec-overloading-on-return-type"></emu-xref>), and the lane counts an implementation can hold in a register.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>generics</td><td>Value generic parameters and their arguments; the `where` clause; declaration-site variance, which <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref> leaves open; the syntax of a computed value type argument, which <emu-xref href="#sec-type-references"></emu-xref> does not provide; and the checking of a generic body, within which a reference to an unbound parameter appears in a deferred application as its declaring Parse Node and is substituted at specialization (<emu-xref href="#sec-deferred-applications"></emu-xref>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>dependent record types</td><td>The `is` operator, which <emu-xref href="#table-narrowing-forms"></emu-xref> lists as a narrowing form, and the `where` clauses whose run-time check is inserted at the boundaries of <emu-xref href="#table-check-sites"></emu-xref>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>decorators</td><td>The reflection facility of which <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-getreflection"></emu-xref> is one context, including the reflection of a declaration's members and a function's signatures.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>complex numbers</td><td>The type of an imaginary literal (<emu-xref href="#sec-imaginary-literals"></emu-xref>) and the conversions of the complex types.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>operator overloading</td><td>The declaration syntax for an operator and the resolution of a case where the receiver is not the left operand.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>threading</td><td>The sharing of a value across Agents, which <emu-xref href="#sec-gettypeobject"></emu-xref> notes is the only route by which a Type Object leaves its Agent.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>ranges</td><td>The case ranges a `switch` over a float discriminant requires, and the bounded `for` whose counter <emu-xref href="#sec-check-elision"></emu-xref> relies on to prove an index in range.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>type programming</td><td>The standard builder kit as a module and its normative status; the evaluable fragment as a normative annex with its conformance suite; symbol values as literal types, which <emu-xref href="#sec-literal-types"></emu-xref> excludes; the `matchType` convenience; and the contextual rules that consume a signature's [[ThisType]] and a declared narrowing, the data half of which <emu-xref href="#sec-signature-records"></emu-xref> now carries for `this`. The construction, relations, `never`, and evaluation obligations recorded here previously are discharged by <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-maketype"></emu-xref>, <emu-xref href="#sec-reflect-isassignable"></emu-xref>, <emu-xref href="#sec-never-type"></emu-xref>, and <emu-xref href="#sec-compile-time-evaluability"></emu-xref>.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </emu-table>

      <emu-note>
        <p>The extensions not listed, including serialization, structure of arrays, the regular expression types, Temporal, and the standard library, are specified in terms of the core and are relied on by nothing here.</p>
        <p>The dependency runs in one direction with one exception. The metadata parameterization of the primitive metadata extension is relied on by <emu-xref href="#sec-issubtype"></emu-xref>, which is the keystone of the core, so the subtyping of a primitive cannot be stated without a forward reference to an extension. This is the one place where the core and an extension are not separable, and it is worth deciding whether the parameterization belongs in the core instead. The same rule already has to cover an enum refining its underlying type (<emu-xref href="#sec-enums"></emu-xref>), which is core, so the relation is not an extension's to own.</p>
      </emu-note>
    </emu-clause>
  </emu-clause>
</emu-clause>
